{"title_page": "September Massacres", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2011}}\n[[File:1797 Jean Map of Paris and the Faubourgs, France - Geographicus - Paris-jean-1797.jpg|thumb|270px|Map of Paris and the Faubourgs (1797). The [[La Force prison]] was in [[Le Marais]] on Rue Pav\u00e9e, near [[Place des Vosges|Place des F\u00e9d\u00e9r\u00e9s]]. The [[Conciergerie]] was located on the westside of the [[\u00cele de la Cit\u00e9]], next to the [[Palais de Justice, Paris|Palais de Justice]].]] \n[[File:Massacre \u00e0 la Salp\u00eatri\u00e8re.jpg|thumb|270px|The [[Salp\u00eatri\u00e8re]] hospital where 35 women were killed.]]\n[[File:H\u00f4pital Royal de Bic\u00eatre, Paris; panoramic view with gardens Wellcome L0003004.jpg|thumb|270px|The royal hospital [[Bic\u00eatre]] where 150-170 men were killed.]]\n\nThe '''September Massacres''' were a series of killings of prisoners in Paris that occurred from 2\u20136 September 1792 during the [[French Revolution]].  They lasted from Sunday afternoon until Thursday evening. [[Charlotte Corday]] held [[Jean-Paul Marat]] responsible, but for [[Madame Roland]] it was [[Georges Danton]].<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=PaN4DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA97&lpg=PA97&dq=charlotte+corday+marat+responsible+september+massacre&source=bl&ots=egZw2jch2B&sig=ACfU3U3WvsIr1aaCoH2ohd6aXPJHcPTKww&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj02_C_vfPmAhXCYlAKHUyuAkcQ6AEwBnoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=charlotte%20corday%20marat%20responsible%20september%20massacre&f=false Watanabe-O'Kelly, H. (2018) From Viragos to Valkyries Transformations of the Heroic Warrior Woman in German literature from the Seventeenth to the Nineteenth Century. In: Tracing the Heroic Through Gender]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=fIZBE5JmbJUC&pg=PT98&hl=de&source=gbs_toc_r&cad=4#v=onepage&q=Massacre%20poisened&f=false The Giant of the French Revolution: Danton, A Life by David Lawday]</ref> Danton was also accused by the French historians [[Adolphe Thiers]], [[Alphonse Lamartine]], [[Jules Michelet]], [[Louis Blanc]] and [[Edgar Quinet]]. According to [[Albert Soboul]] there is no proof, however, that the massacres were organized by Danton or by anyone else, though it is certain that he did nothing to stop them.<ref>[https://www.britannica.com/biography/Georges-Danton/Dantons-Committee-of-Public-Safety Britannica.com]</ref> \n\nIt is estimated that around 1,100-1,600 people were murdered. The action was undertaken by 235<ref>[https://archive.org/details/histoiredesgiron02gran/page/312 <!-- quote=187. --> Adolphe Granier de Cassagnac (1860) Histoire Des Girondins Et Des Massacres de Septembre, Band 2, p. 29-30]</ref> ''[[F\u00e9d\u00e9r\u00e9]]s'', [[National Guard (France)|Guardsmen]] and [[Sansculottes]], with the support of [[National Gendarmerie|Gendarmes]], the latter were responsible for guarding the tribunals and prisons,<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=QTg_AAAAcAAJ&pg=PA417&lpg=PA417&dq=couvre-feu+28+aout+1792&source=bl&ots=_HF3YHDGtQ&sig=2-EsOuOC3t74zR8_vrGMdsqlSXo&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwipyJLx-Z7fAhWDCewKHaF-A-sQ6AEwDHoECAMQAQ#v=onepage&q=31%20AOUT&f=false Collection Compl\u00e8te des Lois, D\u00e9crets, Ordonnances, R\u00e9glements, p. 458]</ref> the [[Cordeliers]], the Insurrectional Commune and the [[Revolutionary sections of Paris]].<ref>P. Caron (1935), p. 107, 114</ref><ref>S. Schama, p. 611</ref><ref>[https://warwick.ac.uk/fac/arts/history/students/modules/comparative_revolutions/programme/frenchrev2/furet_terror.pdf F. Furet & M. Ozouf (1989) A Critical Dictionary of the French Revolution, p. 139]</ref><ref>Adolphe Granier de Cassagnac (1862?) Histoire des Girondins et des Massacres de Septembre, p. ?</ref> We will never know the identity of the \"septembriseurs\". But a large number of them were undoubtedly Parisian national guards and provincial federates who remained in the city since their arrival in July.<ref>[https://www.lhistoire.fr/septembre-1792-de-la-rumeur-au-massacre Septembre 1792 : de la rumeur au massacre by T. Tackett]</ref> By 6 September, half the prison population of Paris had been summarily executed. The exact number is not known; about 440-500 people had uncertain fates, including 200 Swiss soldiers.<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=DvlXDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT1&lpg=PT1&dq=Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric+Bluche,+Septembre+1792+:+logiques+d%27un+massacre&source=bl&ots=a1sr2GXf7z&sig=cvmJ82u26SEUyukTQEcyz0XJ0IM&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjwnIGQqbXeAhXNFsAKHZCoALUQ6AEwCHoECAEQAQ#v=onepage&q=Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric%20Bluche%2C%20Septembre%201792%20%3A%20logiques%20d'un%20massacre&f=false Septembre 1792 : logiques d'un massacre by Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Bluche (1986), p. ?]</ref><ref>[https://ia801409.us.archive.org/2/items/larvolution00madeuoft/larvolution00madeuoft.pdf L. Madelin, p. 256]</ref> However, the great majority (72%) of those killed were non-political prisoners - galley convicts, [[forgery|forgers]] of [[assignats]], common criminals, women, and children; 17% were Catholic priests.<ref>{{cite book|author=Gwynne Lewis|title=The French Revolution: Rethinking the Debate|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gNIHpeoORmQC&pg=PA38|year=2002|publisher=Routledge|page=38}}</ref><ref>Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Bluche (1986) Septembre 1792 : logiques d'un massacre, p. 235</ref> The Minister of Interior [[Jean-Marie Roland de la Plati\u00e8re|Roland]] accused the Commune of the atrocities. According to [[Georges Lefebvre]] the collective mentality is a [[sufficient]] explanation for the killing.<ref name=\"Georges Lefebvre 2001\">Georges Lefebvre, ''The French Revolution: From its Origins to 1793'' (2001) p.236</ref> For [[Timothy Tackett]] \"the obsession with a prison conspiracy, the desire for revenge, the fear of the advancing Prussians, the ambiguity over who was in control of a state that had always relied in the past on a centralized monarchy: all had come together in a volatile mixture of anger, fear, and uncertainty.\"<ref>[https://h-france.net/rude/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/TackettVol4.pdf Tackett, Timothy (2011) \"Rumor and Revolution: The Case of the September Massacres\", ''French History and Civilization'' Vol. 4, pp. 54\u201364.]</ref>\n\nThere was a fear that foreign and royalist armies would attack Paris and that the (Swiss) inmates of the city's prisons would be freed and join them. On 1 September [[National Legislative Assembly (France)|Legislative Assembly]] called for volunteers who gathered the next day on the [[Champs de Mars]].<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=QTg_AAAAcAAJ&pg=PA459&dq=1+Septembre+1792+paris&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwinyK-viejmAhWIPFAKHQ0GBU84FBDoAQhKMAQ#v=onepage&q=1%20Septembre%201792%20paris&f=false Collection Compl\u00e8te des Lois, D\u00e9crets, Ordonnances, R\u00e9glements, p. 459-460]</ref> On Sunday 2 September around 13:00, [[Georges Danton|Danton]], a member of the provisional government, delivered a speech in the assembly: \u201cWe ask that any one refusing to give personal service or to furnish arms shall be punished with death\u201d.<ref>[http://www2.assemblee-nationale.fr/decouvrir-l-assemblee/histoire/grands-discours-parlementaires/danton-2-septembre-1792 Assembl\u00e9e Nationale]</ref> \u201cThe bell we are about to ring is not an alarm signal; it sounds the charge on the enemies of our country\". After applause he continued, \u201cTo conquer them we must dare, dare again, always dare, and France is saved!\u201d.<ref>[https://www.bartleby.com/268/7/20.html  The World\u2019s Famous Orations. Continental Europe (380\u20131906).  1906.]</ref><ref>[https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k54946638.texteImage Discours de Danton : Edition critique par Andr\u00e9 Fribourg, p. 172. Paris Au si\u00e9ge de la Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 1910.]</ref> His speech acted as a call for direct action among the citizens, as well as a strike against the external enemy.<ref>[https://www.lrb.co.uk/the-paper/v31/n15/hilary-mantel/he-roared [[Hillary Mantel]] in London Review of Books]</ref> <!--In reality Danton was probably speaking of boldness needed in fighting the war but some French citizens took it as boldness needed in fighting within France to those who were viewed as \u201ctraitors\u201d and killing occurred all over the streets.<ref>[http://westerncivguides.umwblogs.org/2011/09/25/jacobins-vs-girondins-during-the-french-revolution/]</ref>  -->  Many believe this speech was responsible for inciting the September Massacres.\n\nThe  massacre began around 14:30 in the middle of [[Saint-Germain-des-Pr\u00e9s#The French Revolution|Saint-Germain-des-Pr\u00e9s]]. Within the first 20 hours more than 1,000 prisoners were killed. The next morning on 3 September the <!--Assembly authorized employees to leave office and defend the country. The--> surveillance committees of the Commune, on which Marat now served, published a circular that called on provincial Patriots to defend Paris and asked that, before leaving their homes, they eliminate counter-revolutionaries. The secretary of the Commune, [[Jean-Lambert Tallien]] called on other cities to follow suit.<ref>F. Furet and M. Ozouf, eds. ''A Critical Dictionary of the French Revolution'' (1989), pp. 521\u201322</ref> The massacres were repeated in a few other French cities; in total 65-75 incidents were reported.<ref>P. Caron (1935) Les massacres de Septembre, p. 363-394. Part IV covers comparable events in provincial cities that transpired from July to October 1792.</ref><ref>P. McPhee (2016) Liberty or Death, p. 162</ref> \n\n==Background==\n===The Duke of Brunswick's manifesto=== \n\n[[File:Le Grand Ch\u00e2telet vu depuis la rue Saint-Denis, 1800.jpg|thumb|200px|The [[Grand Ch\u00e2telet]] from the north where about 220 people were killed.]]\n[[File:Porte Saint-Bernard Adam Perelle.jpg|thumb|200px|[[Ch\u00e2teau de la Tournelle|Saint-Bernard]] where 75 men (forgers?) convicted to the galley were killed.]]\n[[File:St firmin.jpg|thumb|200px|Saint Firmin in the Rue Saint Victor were 73 seminarians were killed.]]\n\nIn April 1792 France declared war on the [[Habsburg Monarchy]], prompting the [[War of the First Coalition]]. In July, an army under the [[Charles William Ferdinand, Duke of Brunswick-Wolfenb\u00fcttel|Duke of Brunswick]] and composed mostly of [[Kingdom of Prussia|Prussians]] joined the Austrian side and invaded France. As the army advanced, Paris went into a state of hysteria, especially after the Duke issued the \"[[Brunswick Manifesto]]\" on 25 July. His avowed aim was\n<blockquote>to put an end to the anarchy in the interior of France, to check the attacks upon the throne and the altar, to reestablish the legal power, to restore to the king the security and the liberty of which he is now deprived and to place him in a position to exercise once more the legitimate authority which belongs to him.<ref>{{cite book|author=Arno J. Mayer|title=The Furies: Violence and Terror in the French and Russian Revolutions|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gveBKGhmskAC&pg=PA554|year=2000|publisher=Princeton U.P.|page=554}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nThe Manifesto threatened the French population with instant punishment should it resist the Imperial and Prussian armies, or the reinstatement of the monarchy. The Manifesto was frequently described as unlawful and offensive to national sovereignty. Its authorship was frequently in doubt. Revolutionaries like Marat and H\u00e9bert suggested to concentrate on the internal enemy.<ref>[https://www.academia.edu/915802/_The_Myth_of_the_Foreign_Enemy_The_Brunswick_Manifesto_and_the_Radicalization_of_the_French_Revolution_French_History_25_no._2_2011_188-213?email_work_card=view-paper \"The Myth of the Foreign Enemy? The Brunswick Manifesto and the Radicalization of the French Revolution,\" French History 25, no. 2 (2011): 188-213 by Elisabeth Cross]</ref> On 3 August P\u00e9tion and 47 sections demanded the deposition of the king.\n\n===The insurrection of the Paris commune===\nOn the evening of 9 August 1792, a [[Jacobin]] insurrection overthrew the leadership of the Paris municipality, proclaiming a new [[Paris Commune (French Revolution)|revolutionary Commune]] headed by transitional authorities. The next day the insurrectionists [[10 August (French Revolution)|stormed the Tuileries Palace]]. King [[Louis XVI of France|Louis XVI]] was imprisoned with the royal family, and his authority as King was suspended by the [[National Legislative Assembly (France)|\nLegislative Assembly]]. The next day the royalist press was silenced. A provisional executive (Conseil ex\u00e9cutif) was named and busied itself with reorganizing or solving questions concerning the police, justice, the army, navy and paper money but actual power now rested with the new revolutionary Commune, whose strength resided in the mobilized and armed ''[[sans-culottes]]'', the lower classes of Paris, and ''[[f\u00e9d\u00e9r\u00e9s]]'', armed volunteers from the provinces that had arrived at the end of July. The 48 sections of Paris were equipped with munitions from the plundered arsenals in the days before the assault, substituting for the 60 National Guard battalions. Supported by a new armed force, the Commune dominated the Legislative Assembly and its decisions.<ref>Bergeron, Louis, ''Le Monde et son Histoire'', Paris, 1970, Volume VII, Chapter VII, p. 324</ref> The Commune pushed through several measures: universal suffrage was adopted, the civilian population was armed, all remnants of noble privileges were abolished and the [[Biens nationaux|properties]] of the ''[[\u00e9migr\u00e9s]]'' were sold. These events meant a change of direction from the political and constitutional perspective of the [[Girondists]] to a more social approach given by the Commune as expressed by [[Pierre-Joseph Cambon]]: \"To reject with more efficacy the defenders of despotism, we have to address the fortunes of the poor, we have to associate the Revolution with this multitude that possesses nothing, we have to convert the people to the cause.\"<ref>L. Bergeron (1970), p. 325.</ref>\n\nBesides these measures, the Commune engaged in a policy of political repression of all suspected counter-revolutionary activities. Beginning on 11 August, every Paris section named surveillance committees (Committees of Vigilance), which conducting searches and making arrests.<ref>[https://warwick.ac.uk/fac/arts/history/students/modules/comparative_revolutions/programme/frenchrev2/furet_terror.pdf F. Furet & M. Ozouf (1989) A Critical Dictionary of the French Revolution, p. 139]</ref> It was mostly these decentralized committees, rather than the Commune as a whole, which engaged in the repression of August and September 1792. Within a few days each section elected three commissioners to take seat in the insurrectionary Commune, chaired by [[Maximilien Robespierre]]. To ensure that there was some appropriate legal process for dealing with suspects accused of political crimes and treason, rather than arbitrary killing by local committees, a [[Revolutionary Tribunal|revolutionary tribunal]], with extraordinary powers to impose the death sentence without any [[appeal]]<ref>In 1815, a secretary of the Convention, writing under the pseudonyme ''Proussinale'', published some remarkable details about the procedure, [https://books.google.nl/books?id=IV8IAAAAQAAJ&pg=PP11&lpg=PP11&dq=proussinalle&source=bl&ots=wclT9Bbqol&sig=qjJTWyG0P6SnNlqImc5wnraDuvs&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiL3NGouZzfAhWFJ1AKHb4rB1YQ6AEwD3oECAQQAQ#v=onepage&q=robespierre&f=false Histoire secr\u00e8te du tribunal r\u00e9volutionnaire, par M. de Proussinalle, Band 1, p. 2-6]</ref>, was installed on 17 August.<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=y2vy9y9LDvwC&pg=PA277&lpg=PA277&dq=17+august+1792+tribunal+danton&source=bl&ots=M2HaPKgaIo&sig=xBzJDnu4p-C8u4mLOxoCnpK5cew&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiYh42u_5nfAhWosKQKHeE8CGU4ChDoATAHegQICBAB#v=onepage&q=17%20august%201792%20tribunal%20danton&f=false Press in the French Revolution, p. 277]</ref> Robespierre, who had proposed this measure, refused to preside over the tribunal, arguing that the same man ought not to be a denouncer, an accuser, and a judge.<ref name=\"Scurr\">{{cite book|author=Ruth Scurr|author-link=Ruth Scurr |title=Fatal Purity: Robespierre and the French Revolution|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CojtKDmS_ocC|date=17 April 2007|publisher=Henry Holt and Company|isbn=978-0-8050-8261-6}}</ref>{{rp|201}} \n\nAlready on 15 August four sections called for all priests and imprisoned suspects to be put to death before the volunteers departed. Robespierre proposed to erect a pyramid on [[Place Vend\u00f4me]] to remember the victims of 10 August. On 19 August the [[Civil Constitution of the Clergy#Jurors and non-jurors|nonjuring]] priests were ordered to leave the country within two weeks, which meant before 2 September 1792. (In Paris, all monasteries were closed and soon be in use as hospitals, etc. The remaining religious orders were banned by the law of 15 August.<ref>L. Bergeron, p. 326</ref>) [[Jean-Paul Marat|Marat]] left nothing in doubt when he urged \"good citizens to go to the Abbaye, to seize priests, and especially the officers of the Swiss guards and their accomplices and run a sword through them\".<ref>S. Schama, p. 630; L'Amie du peuple, no 680</ref> From 15 to 25 August, around 500 detentions were registered; some were sent to Orl\u00e9ans. Half the detentions were of nonjuring priests, but even priests who had sworn the required oath were caught in the wave.\n\n===Prussian advance and Paris reaction===\n\nOn Sunday, 26th August, news reached Paris that the Prussian army had [[Battle of Verdun (1792)|attacked the key fortress of Verdun]]. [[Jean-Marie Roland de la Plati\u00e8re|Roland]] proposed that the government should leave Paris, whereas Robespierre suggested in a letter to the sections of the Commune that they should defend liberty and equality and maintain their posts, and die if necessary.<ref>[[Jean Massin]] (1959) Robespierre, p. 133-134</ref> The Assembly decreed that all the non-juring priests had to leave Paris within 8 days and the country within two weeks.<ref>Le Moniteur universel, t. XIII, n\u00b0 241, du 28 a\u00f4ut, p. 540</ref>  In the evening, in the presence of 350,000 people, a funeral ceremony was held in the gardens of the Tuileries for those killed while [[Insurrection of 10 August 1792|storming the Tuileries]].<ref>[Le Moniteur universel, t. XIII, n\u00b0 244, du 31 a\u00f4ut, p. 572<]</ref> \n\nOn 28 August, the Assembly ordered a curfew for the next two days.<ref name=\"Massin\"/> On the behest of justice minister Danton, thirty commissioners from the sections were ordered to search in every suspect house for weapons, munition, swords, carriages and horses.<ref>S. Schama, p. 626</ref><ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=QTg_AAAAcAAJ&pg=PA417&lpg=PA417&dq=couvre-feu+28+aout+1792&source=bl&ots=_HF3YHDGtQ&sig=2-EsOuOC3t74zR8_vrGMdsqlSXo&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwipyJLx-Z7fAhWDCewKHaF-A-sQ6AEwDHoECAMQAQ#v=onepage&q=28%20AOUT&f=false Collection Compl\u00e8te des Lois, D\u00e9crets, Ordonnances, R\u00e9glements, p. 440]</ref> Before 2 September, between 520\u20131,000 people were taken into custody on the flimsiest warrants. The exact number of those arrested will never be known.<ref>S. Loomis, p. 77</ref> \n\nOn 29th August, the Prussians took Verdun, gaining a clear westward path to [[Paris]].<ref name=\"Parker2008\">{{Cite book|last=Parker |first=Geoffrey |title=The Cambridge Illustrated History of Warfare |year=2008 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |location=New York |isbn=978-0-521-73806-4 |page=195 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yqNj5BlEMtcC&pg=PA195|accessdate=22 January 2012 }}</ref> When this news arrived two days later it escalated the sense of panic. On 1 September the citizens were told to prepare themselves for the defense of the country and gather immediately on the sound of the tocsin.<ref>Le Moniteur universel, t. XIII, n\u00b0 248, du 5 septembre, p. 590</ref> Their imminent departure from the capital provoked further concern about the crowded prisons, now full of counter-revolutionary suspects who might threaten a city deprived of so many of its defenders.<ref>Cobb, R. & C. Jones (1988) The French Revolution. Voices from a momentous epoch 1789-1795, p. 159</ref>  Marat called for a \"new blood-letting\", larger than the one on 10 August. <!--He stopped publishing [[L'Ami du peuple]] for a few weeks. For a while he published posters printed in the basement of the [[Cordeliers Convent]].<ref>Gottschalk, Louis R. (1927, reissued 1966). Jean-Paul Marat: A Study in Radicalism, Benjamin Bloom, p. 97.</ref>) The four printing press he used came from the Tuileries.--> The British ambassador reported:\n<blockquote>A party at the instigation of someone or other declared they would not quit Paris, as long as the prisons were filled with Traitors (for they called those so, that were confined in the different Prisons and Churches), who might in the absence of such a number of Citizens rise and not only effect the release of His Majesty, but make an entire counterrevolution.<ref>Oscar Browning, ed., ''The Despatches of Earl Gower'' (Cambridge University Press, 1885), 213\u201316, 219\u201321, 223\u201328.</ref></blockquote><!--according to [[Louis-Marie Prudhomme]] \"Marat proposed to set the prisons on fire, but it was pointed out to him that the neighboring houses would be endangered; someone else advised flooding them. Billaud-Varennes proposed butchering the prisoners. [[Jean-Lambert Tallien]], the Commune's secretary-general, showed disgust at the discussion, but did not have the courage to oppose it.\"{{cn|date=December 2019}} [[Marquis de Condorcet|Condorcet]] argued that any \"enemies of the people\" belonged to the Nation and that prisoners ought not be judged by members of the Commune, but by the Nation, earning him the enmity of Marat and Robespierre.{{cn|date=December 2019}} Marat was also furious at Roland, who had refused him a financial subsidy according to [[Louis Madelin]].{{cn|date=December 2019}}-->\n\nThroughout August, the Legislative Asssembly, which had been greatly diminished as more than half of the deputies had fled since the storming of the Tuileries, had acquiesced to the activities of the Commune and its sections. On 30 August, the Girondins Roland and [[Marguerite-\u00c9lie Guadet]] tried to suppress the influence of the Commune, accused of exercising unlawful power. The Assembly, tired of the pressures, declared the Commune illegal and suggested the organization of communal elections and a doubling of the number of seats.<ref name=\"Israel267\">J. Israel (2014), ''Revolutionary Ideas'', p. 267-268.</ref><ref name=\"Massin\">J. Massin (1959), ''Robespierre'', p. 132.</ref> However, the Assembly cancelled the decree the next day at the request of [[Jacques-Alexis Thuriot de la Rosi\u00e8re|Jacques-Alexis Thuriot]]. The balance of power was disrupted and the conflict between the Girondins and the Montagnards would influence the progress of the French Revolution.<ref name=\"Israel267\"/>\n\nOn 1 September, the gates of the city, closed the days before, were opened on the orders of P\u00e9tion, providing an opportunity for suspects to flee the capital. According to [[Louis-Marie Prudhomme]] people still profited from the opportunity on Sunday morning 2 September.<ref>L. Bluche, p. 258</ref> The Assembly decreed to arm the volunteers; a third would stay in Paris and defend the city with pikes, the others were meant for the frontier and the trenches. It further decreed that traitors who refused to participate in the defense or hand over their arms deserved death.<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=QTg_AAAAcAAJ&pg=PA459&dq=1+Septembre+1792+paris&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwinyK-viejmAhWIPFAKHQ0GBU84FBDoAQhKMAQ#v=onepage&q=1%20Septembre%201792%20paris&f=false Collection Compl\u00e8te des Lois, D\u00e9crets, Ordonnances, R\u00e9glements, p. 459-460]</ref> The sections, gathered in the townhall, decided to remain in Paris; Marat proposed to have Roland and his fellow [[Girondists|Girondist]] Brissot arrested.<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=DvlXDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=logiques+d%27un+massacre&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjtvPio06PfAhULC-wKHa30BdwQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=insens\u00e9&f=false Septembre 1792: logiques d'un massacre by Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Bluche]</ref> <!--At noon--> The Commune ordered the gates closed and an alarm gun fired. After the tocsin was rung around 2 o'clock 60,000 men enrolled for the defense of the country on the Champs de Mars. <!--It seems 10,000 were without weapons.-->\n\n==Massacres==\n[[File:Massacres des 2, 3, 4, 5 et 6 septembre 1792.jpg|thumb|200px|[[Prison de l'Abbaye]] where between 160-220 people were killed in three days. It was located between Rue de Bussi and Rue du Four (E40), with the entrance on Rue Sainte-Marguerite, today 133, [[Boulevard Saint-Germain]].]]\n[[File:Stanislas-marie-maillard.jpg|thumb|200px|[[Stanislas-Marie Maillard]] ]]\n[[File:Massacre des Carmes-Bilcocq-IMG 2416.JPG|thumb|200px|115 priests were killed in the [[Carmes prison]]. ''Le massacre des Carmes'' by Marie-Marc-Antoine Bilcocq, (1820). [[Mus\u00e9e de la R\u00e9volution fran\u00e7aise]].]]\n[[File:Conciergerie in 1790.jpg|thumb|200px|[[Conciergerie]] where 250-3,0 people were killed.]]\n[[File:Massacre ch\u00e2telet 1792.jpg|thumb|200px|Mass killing of more than 200 prisoners in the Ch\u00e2telet on 3 September]] \n\nThe first massacre began in [[quartier Latin]] around 2.30 on Sunday afternoon when 24 [[Civil Constitution of the Clergy#Jurors and non-jurors|non-juring priest]]s were being transported to the [[prison de l'Abbaye]] near the [[Abbey of Saint-Germain-des-Pr\u00e9s#Former configuration|Abbey of Saint-Germain-des-Pr\u00e9s]], after being interrogated by [[Billaud-Varenne]] in the townhall. One of the carriages, escorted by F\u00e9d\u00e9r\u00e9s, was attacked after an incident.<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=yDIEAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA268&lpg=PA268&dq=insurrection+french+revolution&source=bl&ots=53T3ZQ6WRN&sig=bkjxrkuajhSUrkdDo5s9yYDBOpU&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj2v6qpwdDdAhWFLewKHeZbAecQ6AEwDXoECAAQAQ#v=onepage&q=Lamballe&f=false The history of the French revolution, tr. with notes by Marie Joseph L. Adolphe Thiers, p. 144]</ref> The F\u00e9d\u00e9r\u00e9s killed three men in the middle of the street, before the procession arrived at the prison. Eighteen arrested were taken inside. They then mutilated the bodies, \"with circumstances of barbarity too shocking to describe\" according to the British diplomatic dispatch. One of their victims was the former Minister of Foreign Affairs [[Armand Marc, comte de Montmorin]]. [[Roch-Ambroise Cucurron Sicard]] was recognized as beneficent priest and released. \n\nIn the late afternoon 115 priests in the [[Carmes prison|former convent of Carmelites]], detained with the message they would be deported to [[French Guiana]], were massacred in the courtyard with axes, spikes, swords and pistols by people (with a strong [[patois]] accent). They forced the priests one by one to take the oath on the [[Civil Constitution of the Clergy]], and \"swear to be faithful to the nation and to maintain liberty and equality or die defending it\".<ref>F. Bluche, p. 219</ref>  The priests hid in the choir and behind the altar. Several tried to escape by climbing in the trees and over the walls and escaped through Rue Cassette.<ref>[https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k65832786.texte Image Les Massacres du 2 septembre 1792 \u00e0 la prison des Carmes \u00e0 Paris, p. ?]</ref><ref>S. Loomis, p. 79</ref> <!--When the L\u00e9gislative became aware of what happened six or seven commissioners were send out to check the other prisons. --> \n\nAround five a group of 200 \"Septembriseurs\" came to the house of Roland on [[Place Dauphine]] to arrest him, but as he was at the Ministry they went there. Between seven and eight o'clock in the evening the group of F\u00e9d\u00e9r\u00e9s, etc. was back at the Abbaye prison. (The Abbaye prison was located in what is now the [[Boulevard Saint-Germain]] just west of the current Passage de la Petite Boucherie.) The door was closed, but the bloody work was resumed after an intense discussion with Manuel, the procurator, on people's justice and failing judges.<ref>F. Bluche, p. 56-60</ref> He belonged to a deputation sent by the Commune to ask for compassion.<ref>L. Blanc (1855) Histoire de la R\u00e9volution Fran\u00e7aise, vol VII, p. 163</ref> They were insulted and escaped with their lives.<ref>Oscar Browning, ed., ''The Despatches of [[George Leveson-Gower, 1st Duke of Sutherland|Earl Gower]]'' (Cambridge University Press, 1885), 213\u201316, 219\u201321, 223\u201328.</ref> A tribunal composed of twelve people, presided by Stanislas-Marie Maillard, started the interrogating by asking the prisoner why he was arrested. A lie was fatal.<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=fAMxAQAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=L.+Blanc+(1855)+Histoire+de+la+R\u00e9volution+Fran\u00e7aise,+vol+VII&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjbpLmghJPfAhWKmbQKHXS-BFMQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=L.%20Blanc%20(1855)%20Histoire%20de%20la%20R\u00e9volution%20Fran\u00e7aise%2C%20vol%20VII&f=false L. Blanc (1855) Histoire de la R\u00e9volution Fran\u00e7aise, vol VII, p. 165]</ref> <!-- 135 Swiss inmates were killed, 27 were transferred, 86 were set free, and 36 had uncertain fates.<ref>Leborgne, Dominique, ''Saint-Germain-des-Pr\u00e9s et son faubourg'', p. 40, \u00c9ditions Parigramme, Paris, 2005, {{ISBN|2-84096-189-X}}</ref> According to [[George Long (scholar)|George Long]] 122 died, 43 people were released.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/franceanditsrev00longgoog/page/n175 <!-- pg=161 quote= Robespierre . --> France and Its Revolutions: A Pictorial History 1789-1848 by George Long, p. 199-202]</ref>--> \n\nIn the early evening groups broke into another Paris prison, the [[Conciergerie]]. According to Prudhomme people sat on the stairs of the Palace of Justice watching the butchery in the courtyard.<ref>F. Bluche, p. 260</ref> Not far away [[Nicolas-Edme Restif de la Bretonne|Restif de la Bretonne]] saw the bodies piled high on [[Pont Notre-Dame|Pont au Change]] in front of the [[Grand Ch\u00e2telet|Ch\u00e2telet]]. The corpses were thrown in the river. He recorded the atrocities he witnessed in ''Les Nuits de Paris'' (1794).<ref>[http://chnm.gmu.edu/revolution/d/392/ The September Massacres witnessed by Restif de la Bretonne]</ref> Late that night they went to [[Ch\u00e2teau de la Tournelle|Tour Saint-Bernard]] where the forgers of assignats were jailed. The pattern of semi-formal executions followed by the popular tribunals was for condemned prisoners to be ordered \"transferred\" or even \"released\" and then taken into the prison courtyards where they would be cut down. \n\nBefore midnight the [[seminary]] Saint Firmin was visited by just four men, who killed all the [[seminarian]]s. At 2.30 in the morning the Assembly was informed that most of the prisons were empty. <!--According to Tallien all prisoners involved in the events of 10 August or producing false assignats were killed.<ref>Le Moniteur universel, t. XIII, n\u00b0 248, du 4 septembre, p. 603</ref>--> The next morning the Assembly was still involved with the defense of the city; [[Marie-Jean H\u00e9rault de S\u00e9chelles|H\u00e9rault de S\u00e9chelles]] presided. It decided the other prisoners had to wait for their trial because of a temporary lack of judges.<ref>Le Moniteur universel, t. XIII, n\u00b0 248, du 5 septembre, p. 607</ref> \n\nAround 4 in the afternoon [[Madame de Sta\u00ebl]], as ambassadress of Sweden, who lived in [[Rue du Bac]] near Champ de Mars, tried to flee through crowded streets but her carriage was stopped and the crowd forced her to go to the [[H\u00f4tel de Ville, Paris|Paris town hall]], where [[Robespierre]] presided.<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=mPANAAAAQAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Sta\u00ebl+Robespierre&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi_v7nI96jeAhXJKVAKHT7lDzAQ6AEIRTAE#v=onepage&q=Sta\u00ebl%20Robespierre&f=false Considerations on the Principal Events of the French Revolution, Band 2, p. 75]</ref> Late in the evening, she was conveyed home, escorted by the [[public procurator|procurator]] [[Louis Pierre Manuel]]. The next day the secretary-general to the [[Paris Commune (French Revolution)|Commune of Paris]], Tallien, arrived with a passport and accompanied her to the [[Barricade|barrier]].<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=r2wBAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA341&lpg=PA341&dq=Manuel+germaine+de+stael&source=bl&ots=ccvAqmorAJ&sig=63s5MOtCsWb34fkom7anFCovO78&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwijiLrX6YXdAhXQ6aQKHYaWBEkQ6AEwEHoECAAQAQ#v=onepage&q=Manuel%20germaine%20de%20stael&f=false A New Dictionary of the French Revolution by Richard Ballard, p. 341]</ref>\n\nOn Monday morning nine o'clock, [[Billaud-Varenne]] came to the Abbaye prison and declared that the murderers should stop stealing and would get paid by the Commune. [[Bic\u00eatre]] (for men and boys) was visited twice that day after a rumor there were thousands of rifles stored. They brought seven cannons with them. The killing went on until the next day. At dawn [[H\u00f4pital de la Salp\u00eatri\u00e8re|Salp\u00eatri\u00e8re]] (for women and girls) was visited.<ref>F. Bluche, p. 193</ref> where prostitutes seem to have been released and young girls raped.<ref>https://www.tombes-sepultures.com/crbst_2169.html#anchor-Massacres</ref> On Tuesday afternoon the killing stopped finally in the Abbey. Police commissioners [[:fr:\u00c9tienne-Jean Panis]] and [[Antoine Louis Fran\u00e7ois Sergent dit Sergent-Marceau|Sergent-Marceau]] gave orders to wash away all the blood from the stairs and the courtyard, to spread straw, to count the corpses and to dispose of them on carts to avoid infections.<ref>L. Blanc, p. 182</ref> A contract was signed with the grave digger of the nearby [[\u00c9glise Saint-Sulpice, Paris]], who also had to purchase [[quicklime]].  On 5 September, the day of the election, it was perfectly quiet in Paris according [[Le Moniteur Universel]].<ref>Le Moniteur universel, t. XIII, n\u00b0 248, du 5 septembre, p. 613</ref> There were still 80 prisoners in \"La Force\". On 6 September the killing finally stopped.<ref>Le Moniteur universel, t. XIII, n\u00b0 251, du 7 septembre, p. 621</ref><ref>F. Bluche, p. 72, 193</ref> The next day the gates were opened, but it was impossible to travel to another d\u00e9partment without a passport.<ref>Le Moniteur universel, t. XIII, n\u00b0 248, du 7 septembre, p. 629</ref>\n\n===Contemporary reports===\n[[File:LaForcePrisonParis.jpg|thumb|200px|[[La Force prison]] where about 165 people were killed in 48 hours.]]\n\nAccording to Galart de Montjoie, a lawyer and a royalist, in those days everyone believed the F\u00e9d\u00e9r\u00e9s from Marseille, Avignon and Brest were involved in the killing.<ref>[http://libx.bsu.edu/cdm/compoundobject/collection/FrnchRev/id/614/rec/8 Histoire de la conjuration de Robespierre, p. 81. Paris, les marchands de nouveaut\u00e9s, 1795 ; Chez Maret, an IV(1796).]</ref><ref>F. Bluche, p. 233</ref><ref>[https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k367704/f1n650.pdf?download=1 L.M. Ternaux (1863) Histoire de la Terreur, 1792-1794, Tome III, p. 126, 224]</ref> About 800-1000 were staying in barrack, but moved supposedly to where events would take place. <!--During the storming of the Tuileries the F\u00e9d\u00e9res were in the front.<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=dD8XcGgMd_QC&dq=robespierre%20d%C3%A9fenseur%20de%20la%20constitution&hl=de&pg=PA572#v=onepage&q=marseillais&f=false Le D\u00e9fenseur de la Constitution, par Maximilien Robespierre, p. 571]</ref> It is not exactly known how many of them were killed; according to [[Axel von Fersen the Younger|Axel Fersen]] 600,<ref>Cobb, R. & C. Jones (1988) The French Revolution. Voices from a momentous epoch 1789-1795, p. 152-153</ref> according to Robespierre only hundred men.<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=dD8XcGgMd_QC&dq=robespierre%20d%C3%A9fenseur%20de%20la%20constitution&hl=de&pg=PA572#v=onepage&q=marseillais&f=falseLe D\u00e9fenseur de la Constitution, par Maximilien Robespierre, p 572]</ref>--> It seems around 300 F\u00e9d\u00e9r\u00e9s from Brest and 500 from Marseille were then lodged in [[Cordeliers Convent]].<ref>Hampson, Norman (1978) Danton (New York: Basil Blackwell), pp. 71\u201372.</ref><ref>S. Schama, p. 605, 611</ref><ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=iSMVAAAAQAAJ&printsec=frontcover&hl=de&source=gbs_atb#v=snippet&q=assignat&f=false Oeuvres, Band 2 von Maximilien Robespierre, p. 118] [https://books.google.nl/books?id=q2NSAAAAcAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Louis+Blanc+1855+Histoire&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiG6PKU6tveAhUPYVAKHfWbA5sQ6AEIMTAB#v=onepage&q&f=false L. Blanc (1855) Histoire de la R\u00e9volution Fran\u00e7aise. Vol. VII, p. 29]</ref> Servan planned to give them military training before using them to supplement the army at the front.\n\n{{quote|The fact is that the reports of conspiracies in the prisons, however improbable, and the constant propaganda about the people\u2019s will and the people\u2019s anger, held everyone in a sort of stupor and gave the impression that this infamous performance was the work of the populace, whereas in reality there were not above 200 criminals.<ref>The memoirs of Madame Roland, p. ? (London: Barrie & Jenkins, translated by Evelyn Shuckburgh (1989)</ref><ref>[http://libx.bsu.edu/cdm/compoundobject/collection/FrnchRev/id/614/rec/8 Histire de la conjugation de Maximilien Robespierre], p. 81</ref>}}\n\n{{quote|Though it is an ascertained fact that the perpetrators of the atrocious murders were but a few; yet it is not so clear that this work was not connived at, or consented to, by a much greater number, and those perhaps in authority; for otherwise, two or three companies of the town guard would have been sufficient to disperse those who were employed on the occasion.<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=MN-vXtoOXokC&printsec=frontcover&dq=perry+historical+sketch+French+revolution&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwil1-Lw8bLfAhUDJ1AKHR2VB7AQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=September&f=false Sampson Perry (1796) An Historical Sketch of the French Revolution: Commencing with Its predisposing causes, and carried on to the acceptation of the Constitution in 1795. Vol II, p. 230]</ref>}}\n\n{{quote|Perry describes the restoration of order after the events, giving the impression that the massacres may even have had a [[cathartic]] effect. He also suggests that France was plagued by fewer foreign enemies afterwards. What emerges therefore from Perry\u2019s report is a view that, if massacres did take place, they occurred not out of spontaneous popular madness but because of comprehensible grievances.<ref>[https://tel.archives-ouvertes.fr/tel-00797967/document Rachel Rogers (2012) Vectors of Revolution : The British Radical Community in Early Republican Paris, 1792-1794, p. 376. Universit\u00e9 Toulouse le Mirail]</ref>}} According to [[Adolphe Thiers]], [[George Long (scholar)|George Long]] and [[Stanley Loomis]] not an outburst of passion, but coldly and carefully organized.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/franceanditsrev00longgoog/page/n175 <!-- pg=161 quote= Robespierre . --> France and Its Revolutions: A Pictorial History 1789-1848 by George Long, p. 206-207]</ref><ref>S. Loomis, p. 74, 81, 96, 143, 207</ref>\n\n{{quote|Rather than being proof of the unprecedented depravity of an entire population, the prison massacres were the explicable result of both the \u201cwrath and fury\u201d of the victims of 10th August and the machinations of the Paris Commune, who gave their tacit consent to the killings.<ref>[[Helen Maria Williams]]\u2019 [[Letters Written in France|Letters from France]] (1792-93), Letter IV, p. 191</ref> Those targeted in the attacks had not been imprisoned unjustly, but had been suspected of having aided the court in its negotiations with foreign princes. In a similar way to Perry, Williams emphasizes the understandable impatience of the people, who had been kept waiting too long for justice after the August Days, when husbands, brothers and fathers had been killed.<ref>[https://tel.archives-ouvertes.fr/tel-00797967/document Rachel Rogers (2012) Vectors of Revolution : The British Radical Community in Early Republican Paris, 1792-1794, p. 402. Universit\u00e9 Toulouse le Mirail]</ref>}}\n\n===Numbers===\n[[File:MassacrePrincessLamballe.jpg|thumb|200px|A propaganda engraving of the September Massacres showing the killing of Priests; nuns and Princess de Lamballe]]\n[[File:Death-of-the-Princess-De-Lamballe-by-Leon-Maxime-Faivre.jpg|thumb|200px|L\u00e9on-Maxime Faivre (1908) Death of the Princess de Lamballe]]\n\nAccording to [[Pierre Caron (historian)|Pierre Caron]] there were almost 2,800 prisoners in early September. Between 1,250-1,450 prisoners were condemned and executed. According to Caron and Bluche 70% of the victims were killed in a 20-hour interval.<ref>F. Bluche, p. 192</ref> Among the victims were 223 [[:wikt:nonjuror|nonjuring]] Catholic priests and (arch)bishops who refused to submit to the [[Civil Constitution of the Clergy]], 81 [[Swiss guards]], and 40-80 political suspects, mostly royalists, aristocrats and some former judges and ministers<ref>P. Caron (1935) Les Massacres de Septembre, p. 94-99; 101-102</ref> including the queen's best friend, the [[Princess Marie Louise of Savoy|''Princesse de Lamballe'']], the only political victim in \"La petite Force\".<ref>[https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k40941v/f4.image The history of the French revolution, tr. with notes by Marie Joseph L. Adolphe Thiers]</ref>\n\nThe lives of about 1,250-1,600 prisoners brought before the people's courts were saved.<ref>P. Caron, p. 99</ref> In a few cases people were acclaimed as \"patriots\" by Robespierre, Tallien, Desmoulins and Danton.<ref>M. J. Sydenham ''The French Revolution'', B.T. Batsford Ltd, 1965, p. 121</ref><ref>L. Michelet, tome IV, p. 121</ref> Several prisoners for debts or alimony were released by Manuel or by the police before 2 September.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/histoiredesgiron02gran/page/312 <!-- quote=187. --> Adolphe Granier de Cassagnac (1860) Histoire Des Girondins Et Des Massacres de Septembre, Band 2, p. 34-35, 44]</ref> [[Louise-\u00c9lisabeth de Cro\u00ff de Tourzel]] was released from [[Port-Royal Abbey, Paris]] on order of the Commune. \n\nA total of nine prisons were violently entered during the five days of the massacres before the killings concluded on the night of 6\u20137 September; four were not visited ([[Sainte-P\u00e9lagie Prison]], [[Prison Saint-Lazare]], [[Square du Temple|Tour du Temple]] and palais Bourbon). About 700 surviving Swiss soldiers, locked up in [[Palais Bourbon]], marched to the townhall to take the oath and joined the volunteers.<ref>Le Moniteur universel, t. XIII, n\u00b0 251, du 7 septembre, p. 621</ref><ref>[https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k367704/f1n650.pdf?download=1 L.M. Ternaux (1863) Histoire de la Terreur, 1792-1794, d'apr\u00e8s des documents authentiques et in\u00e9dits. Tome III, p. 10, 298]</ref> After initially indiscriminate slayings, ad hoc popular tribunals were set up to distinguish between \"enemies of the people\" and those who were innocent, or at least were not perceived as counter-revolutionary threats. In spite of this attempted sifting, an estimated three-quarters of the 1,250\u20131,450 killed were not counter-revolutionaries or \"villains\", but included all the galley convicts, [[Forgery|forgers]] of [[assignats]], 37 women (including the Princess de Lamballe and the book-seller Marie Gredeler, who was accused of murder) and 66 children.<ref>P. Caron (1935) Les Massacres de Septembre, p. 95</ref><ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=NEosW4-twr4C&pg=PA110&lpg=PA110&dq=Marie+Gredeler+1792&source=bl&ots=RNBaUlUhjq&sig=EL7B2Cuh9Bu6tTHQv76xXAcQlYg&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjxhNuZjd3fAhWMa1AKHV2BA6kQ6AEwAnoECAEQAQ#v=onepage&q=Marie%20Gredeler%201792&f=false Demonic: How the Liberal Mob Is Endangering America by Ann Coulter, p. 110]</ref> Some priests and women were of age, about prostitutes or insane not much is known.<ref>Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Bluche (1986) Septembre 1792 : logiques d'un massacre, p. 235</ref>\n\nIn ''Paris in the Terror'', [[Stanley Loomis]] reports that during the massacre at the prison-hospital of [[Bic\u00eatre]], 33 boys aged between 12 and 18 were murdered by a group of 1,500-2,000 people.<ref>S. Loomis, p. 83</ref><ref>F. Bluche, p. 70</ref><ref>L.M. Ternaux, p. 295-296</ref> Mayor P\u00e9tion did not have much influence discussing [[Humanity (virtue)|humanity]] with them.<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=3gpBAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA346&lpg=PA346&dq=salpetriere+1792+septembre&source=bl&ots=Tcde_IezVW&sig=ACfU3U3GfJYAqoLuQFaakTNUfVDaMow5Ow&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiH6fnpupTnAhWHL1AKHeKYBYI4ChDoATADegQIBRAB#v=onepage&q=salpetriere%201792%20septembre&f=false M\u00e9moires sur les journ\u00e9es de septembre, 1792, p. 348 by Fran\u00e7ois de Jourgniac Saint-M\u00e9ard, Paysac Fars marquise de Fausse-Lendry, Sicard (M. l'abb\u00e9, Roch Ambroise Cucurron), Antoine Gabriel Aim\u00e9 Jourdan]</ref> Loomis also reported that afterwards \"girls as young as ten\" were murdered in [[Salp\u00eatri\u00e8re]] institution for women, mentally insane and prostitutes.<ref>{{Cite book| last =Loomis| first =Stanley|authorlink= Stanley Loomis |title =Paris in the Terror| publisher=Dorset Press| year =1964| location =New York| isbn=0-88029-401-9 }}</ref> The number of victims is exactly known: 35 women, including 23 underaged.<ref>F. Bluche, p. 454</ref>\n\n==Killings outside Paris==\nOn 3 September the <!--Assembly authorized employees to leave office and defend the country. The--> surveillance committees of the Commune, on which Marat now served, published a circular that called on provincial Patriots to defend Paris and asked that, before leaving their homes, they eliminate counter-revolutionaries. Marat advised the entire nation \"to adopt this necessary measure\".<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=9lWNCwAAQBAJ&pg=PR14-IA13&lpg=PR14-IA13&dq=the+entire+nation...+will+hasten+to+adopt+this+necessary+measure+French+revolution&source=bl&ots=9mhX7yi_YI&sig=YKfJVFVxpNjGJg9C-rIHm6aGCXQ&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjq7NGZobjeAhXH_aQKHXzQB_cQ6AEwA3oECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=the%20entire%20nation...%20will%20hasten%20to%20adopt%20this%20necessary%20measure%20French%20revolution&f=false The French Revolution: From Enlightenment to Tyranny by Ian Davidson]</ref>  \n\nA circular letter was sent to regional authorities by [[Fran\u00e7ois Louis Michel Chemin Deforgues|Deforgues]], an assistant of Danton, and [[Tallien]], the secretary of the Paris Commune, advising that \"ferocious conspirators detained in the prisons had been put to death by the people\".<ref>{{cite book |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=q9B-AAAAIAAJ&pg=RA2-PA725 |title=Charles Knight's Popular History of England |chapter=The French Revolution |page=725}} in {{cite book |last=Beale |first=Joseph H. |title=Gay's Standard History of the World's Great Nations |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=q9B-AAAAIAAJ |accessdate=31 August 2018 |volume=1 |year=1884 |publisher=W. Gay and Company}}</ref><ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=pm89AAAAYAAJ&pg=PA993&lpg=PA993&dq=tallien+september+massacres&source=bl&ots=a5atwqaCrb&sig=q_VBuzE4MmcylpezCUz-r1yrSl0&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjqhsf7kZPfAhVCK1AKHRjOAHQ4ChDoATANegQICRAB#v=onepage&q=tallien%20september%20massacres&f=false A general biographical dictionary: containing a summary ..., p. 993 by John Gorton]</ref><ref>[http://www.nndb.com/people/405/000098111/ Jean-Lambert Tallien]</ref> \n\nThe Girondins afterwards made much of this circular, but there is no evidence that it had any influence. As before, murders in the provinces continued: the blood-letting did not cease until the countryside was [[purged]]. <!--According to [[Georges Lefebvre]] the collective mentality is sufficient explanation for the killing.<ref name=\"Georges Lefebvre 2001\">Georges Lefebvre, ''The French Revolution: From its Origins to 1793'' (2001) p. 236</ref>--> Smaller-scale executions took place in Reims, [[Meaux]], and Lyon on 2, 4 and 9 September. <!--There were 75 separate incidents in 32 of France's 83 [[Departments of France|d\u00e9partments]].--> Most notable was the killing of 44 political prisoners near [[Ch\u00e2teau de Versailles]] transported from the High Court in Orl\u00e9ans back to Paris, the [[9 September massacres]].<ref>P. McPhee (2016) Liberty or Death, p. 162</ref> The next day Brissot wrote in \"Le Patriote fran\u00e7ais\", his newspaper: \"No doubt you will be told that it is a vengeance of the people; it will be a slander. The people were not involved in this event.\"<ref>F. Bluche, p. 256</ref>\n\n==Official role==\n\nAccording to [[Timothy Tackett]]:  \"For a period of some 48 hours between the 29th and the 31st of August the whole of Paris was systematically searched by the national guard for lurking conspirators and hidden arms.<ref>\"T. Tackett, p. 63</ref> By that time section assemblies were already passing motions demanding \"the death of conspirators before the departure of citizens\".<ref>S. Schama, p. 631</ref> \n\nOn 31 August the Committee of Vigilance was created with Panis and Sergent-Marceau. According to [[Madame de Sta\u00ebl]] on 31 August \"it was already known, that only those who were destined to be massacred were sent to that prison [of the Abbey].\"<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=mPANAAAAQAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Sta\u00ebl+Robespierre&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi_v7nI96jeAhXJKVAKHT7lDzAQ6AEIRTAE#v=onepage&q=destined%20to%20be%20massacred&f=false Considerations on the Principal Events of the French Revolution, Band 2, p. 68-70]</ref> \n\nOn 1 September the Commune declared a state of emergency by decreeing that on the following day the tocsin should be rung, all able-bodied citizens convened in the Champ de Mars.<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=QTg_AAAAcAAJ&pg=PA459&dq=1+Septembre+1792+paris&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwinyK-viejmAhWIPFAKHQ0GBU84FBDoAQhKMAQ#v=onepage&q=1%20Septembre%201792%20paris&f=false Collection Compl\u00e8te des Lois, D\u00e9crets, Ordonnances, R\u00e9glements, p. 459-460]</ref><!--The next day a decree passed in the Assembly to arm those 60,000 men and traitors who refused to participate in the defence or hand over their arms deserved death.<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=QTg_AAAAcAAJ&pg=PA459&dq=1+Septembre+1792+paris&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwinyK-viejmAhWIPFAKHQ0GBU84FBDoAQhKMAQ#v=onepage&q=1%20Septembre%201792%20paris&f=false Collection Compl\u00e8te des Lois, D\u00e9crets, Ordonnances, R\u00e9glements, p. 459-460]</ref>-->\nOn Sunday 2 September the [[1792 French National Convention election]] started. Robespierre publicly accused [[Brissot]] and the [[Brissotins]] of plotting with the Duke of Brunswick.<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=grUD3hWUc0AC&pg=PA56&lpg=PA56&dq=robespierre+september+massacres&source=bl&ots=zba6lKhLEu&sig=qm5IHGeu4dSUud_FDRRLKBF1N3o&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjplfTdz6PeAhXL_KQKHUASB_YQ6AEwDHoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=robespierre%20september%20massacres&f=false Robespierre by John Hardman, p. 56-57]</ref> Marat was appointed as one of the six additional members of the Committee of Vigilance, but without the approval of the Executive Council.<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=UV5WAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA585&lpg=PA585&dq=comit%C3%A9+de+surveillance+Marat+1792&source=bl&ots=KWgyQgUb0B&sig=ACfU3U16Vw5sfg6XF8l0mbadjALR1xDxrg&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj2h6fh4uLmAhWFGuwKHZ0iBd8Q6AEwAXoECAsQAQ#v=onepage&q=comit%C3%A9%20de%20surveillance%20Marat%201792&f=false Action politique de Marat pendant la R\u00e9volution: (1789-1793) by Jacques De Cock, p. 538 ]</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Adolphe Thiers]] on Sunday morning 2 September: \"The keeper of the Abbaye sent away his children in the morning. Dinner was served to the prisoners two hours before the accustomed time; and the knives were taken from their plates.\"<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=yDIEAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA268&lpg=PA268&dq=insurrection+french+revolution&source=bl&ots=53T3ZQ6WRN&sig=bkjxrkuajhSUrkdDo5s9yYDBOpU&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj2v6qpwdDdAhWFLewKHeZbAecQ6AEwDXoECAAQAQ#v=onepage&q=Dinner%20was%20served&f=false The history of the French revolution, tr. with notes by Marie Joseph L. Adolphe Thiers, p. 144]</ref><ref>[https://archive.org/details/histoiredesgiron02gran/page/312 <!-- quote=187. --> Adolphe Granier de Cassagnac (1860) Histoire Des Girondins Et Des Massacres de Septembre, Band 2, p. 35-36, 53]</ref>\n\nSuch municipal and central government as existed in Paris in September 1792 was preoccupied with organizing volunteers, supplies, and equipment for the armies on the threatened frontiers. Accordingly, there was no attempt to assuage popular fears that the understaffed and easily accessed prisons were full of royalists who would break out and seize the city when the national guards and other citizen volunteers had left for the war. According to Madame Roland Danton responded to an appeal to protect the prisoners with the comment: \"To hell with the prisoners! They must look after themselves.\"<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=LEUuDAAAQBAJ&pg=PT172&lpg=PT172&dq=Discours+de+Danton,+%C3%A9dition+critique,+Paris,+1910&source=bl&ots=whpB9wTshS&sig=ACfU3U1IHSFzzGpCtwpYFLC6j-OP_UQ8zw&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiq86qLrPnmAhVNJlAKHbIjBZQQ6AEwD3oECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=2%20septembre&f=false Danton: Le mythe et l'histoire by Michel Biard, Herv\u00e9 Leuwers]</ref><ref>M. J. Sydenham ''The French Revolution'', B. T. Batsford Ltd, 1965, p. 121</ref><ref>R. Scurr (2006) Fatal Purity. Robespierre and the French Revolution, p. 243?</ref> On 3 September Roland said: \"Yesterday was a day that we should perhaps throw a veil on.\" The other member of the provisional government - [[\u00c9tienne Clavi\u00e8re|Clavi\u00e8re]], [[Pierre Henri H\u00e9l\u00e8ne Marie Lebrun-Tondu|Lebrun-Tondu]], [[Gaspard Monge|Monge]] and [[Joseph Marie Servan de Gerbey|Servan]], involved in organizing the country did not do much to stop the killing, or could not foresee or prevent these excesses. Mayor [[J\u00e9r\u00f4me P\u00e9tion de Villeneuve|P\u00e9tion de Villeneuve]] turned a blind eye when he visited Bic\u00eatre.<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=3gpBAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA346&lpg=PA346&dq=salpetriere+1792+septembre&source=bl&ots=Tcde_IezVW&sig=ACfU3U3GfJYAqoLuQFaakTNUfVDaMow5Ow&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiH6fnpupTnAhWHL1AKHeKYBYI4ChDoATADegQIBRAB#v=onepage&q=salpetriere%201792%20septembre&f=false M\u00e9moires sur les journ\u00e9es de septembre, 1792, p. 348 by  Fran\u00e7ois de Jourgniac Saint-M\u00e9ard, Paysac Fars marquise de Fausse-Lendry, Sicard (M. l'abb\u00e9, Roch Ambroise Cucurron), Antoine Gabriel Aim\u00e9 Jourdan]</ref> [[Olympe de Gouges]] and Brissot's newspaper were the only ones condemning the September murders.\n\n==Debate in the Convention==\n<!--P\u00e9tion was elected as president of the Convention on 20 September 1792.-->The Brissotins in the Convention first attacked Danton; he was asked to resign as minister on the 25th but forced to step down on 9 October. He kept his seat in Convention as deputy. Then the Brissotins decided to attack Robespierre and Marat. \n\nOn 29 October 1792, the Convention held an afterthought. [[Jean-Baptiste Louvet de Couvray]] accused Robespierre of creating a personality cult and interested in governing.<ref>S. Schama p. 649</ref> Robespierre was taken by surprise and had to be defended by Danton.<ref>R. Scurr (2006) Fatal Purity. Robespierre and the French Revolution, p. ?</ref> Robespierre was given eight days to reply. Marat was accused of being asocial and establishing dictatorship. On 5 November Robespierre stated that Marat had visited him only once since January.<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=iSMVAAAAQAAJ&printsec=frontcover&hl=de&source=gbs_atb#v=onepage&q&f=false Oeuvres, Band 2 by Maximilien Robespierre, p. 186, 188]</ref> He admitted the arrests [at the end of August] were illegal, as illegal as the revolution, the fall of the monarchy and the Bastille.<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=iLbxdDTtvvYC&pg=PA213&lpg=PA213&dq=29+october+1792+Robespierre+convention+illegal&source=bl&ots=YeB9T0c2Wt&sig=ACfU3U1TwVY2gmEQ6oqXPEYPwnnoEob4XQ&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwizuvvevf3mAhXIzaQKHXPLDzsQ6AEwBHoECAwQAQ#v=onepage&q=29%20october%201792%20Robespierre%20convention%20illegal&f=false The Eclectic Magazine of Foreign Literature, Science, and Art, Band 3, p. 213]</ref> He asked the Convention: \"Citizens, did you want a revolution without revolution?\" Robespierre, Danton and Marat insisted that the \"new bloodletting\" had been a spontaneous popular movement. Their opponents, the Girondins, spoke of a systematically planned conspiracy.<ref>J. Israel (2014) Revolutionary ideas, p. 271, 273</ref> Roland and Louvet were no longer admitted to the [[Jacobin Club]].<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=UT7WpHqpYbEC&pg=PA53&lpg=PA53&dq=Louvet+expelled+Jacobin+1792&source=bl&ots=69_VFweUSI&sig=ACfU3U0B0VVlIu9vL4xt39S7xHkcXxn0rA&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwivnpaRsODmAhVI3aQKHe4gBwQQ6AEwAHoECAYQAQ#v=onepage&q=Louvet%20expelled%20Jacobin%201792&f=false The Jacobin Republic 1792-1794 by Marc Bouloiseau, p. 53]</ref> \n\nThe political repercussions first injured the [[Girondin]]s (who seemed too moderate) and later the [[Jacobin]]s (who seemed too bloodthirsty).<ref>Georges Lefebvre, ''The French Revolution: From its Origins to 1793'' (1962), pp. 241\u201344, 269</ref> A new mayor [[Nicolas Chambon]] was installed on 1 December 1792. On 20 January 1793 Robespierre defended the massacres as necessary.<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=6wPSAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA263&lpg=PA263&dq=20+janvier+1793+massacre&source=bl&ots=0vTic9B0ur&sig=ACfU3U3KOxgO1eb0Upxc7ookM373-i3spA&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj1-obsrJrnAhVDLlAKHT4yBtAQ6AEwAXoECAsQAQ#v=onepage&q=20%20janvier%201793%20massacre&f=false Oeuvres de Maximilien Robespierre, Band 9 by Maximilien Robespierre,p. 263-264]</ref> [[Louis XVI]] was guillotined on the next day. \n\nIt was Servan's proposal to bring armed volunteers from the provinces. He was arrested during the [[Reign of Terror|Terror]], but released in February 1795. In 1796 24 or 39 craftsmen and small businessmen were accused;<ref>P. Caron (1935), p. 107</ref> though only three were condemned.<ref>F. Bluche, p. 187, 210</ref> The vinegar maker Damiens got twenty years of imprisonment imposed.\n\n==Martyrs==\n{{Main|Holy September Martyrs}}\n[[Image:PrisonAbbayeChapel.jpg|thumb|200px|The abbey chapel in 1793.]]\nA group of 115 [[Clergy|churchmen]] killed in the Carmes Prison was [[Beatification|beatified]] by [[Pope Pius XI]] on 17 October 1926. Among the [[martyrs]] were Pierre-Louis de la Rochefoucauld, [[Ancient Diocese of Saintes|bishop of Saintes]]; [[Jean Marie du Lau|Jean-Marie du Lau d\u2019Alleman]], [[Ancient Diocese of Arles|archbishop of Arles]]; Fran\u00e7ois-Joseph de la Rochefoucauld, [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Beauvais|bishop of Beauvais]]; and [[Ambroise Chevreux]], the last superior-general of the monastic [[Congregation of Saint Maur]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://nominis.cef.fr/contenus/saint/1784/Saints-Martyrs-de-Septembre.html |title=Bienheureux Martyrs des Carmes |language=fr |website=Nominis |publisher=[[Catholic Church in France]] |access-date=2018-08-31 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Notes and citations==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n\n* [https://books.google.nl/books?id=fAMxAQAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=L.+Blanc+(1855)+Histoire+de+la+R\u00e9volution+Fran\u00e7aise,+vol+VII&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjbpLmghJPfAhWKmbQKHXS-BFMQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=L.%20Blanc%20(1855)%20Histoire%20de%20la%20R\u00e9volution%20Fran\u00e7aise%2C%20vol%20VII&f=false Blanc, L. (1855) Histoire de la R\u00e9volution Fran\u00e7aise, vol. VII. FUREURS DE LA GIRONDE]\n* Bluche, F. (1986) Septembre 1792 : logiques d'un massacre.\n* [[Pierre Caron (historian)|Caron, P.]] (1935) ''Les Massacres de Septembre'' \n* [https://books.google.nl/books?id=xpIpAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA272&dq=Robespierre++Temple+prison+September+1792&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjm56eAm_3fAhVLZVAKHUQABOcQ6AEIODAC#v=onepage&q=Robespierre%20%20Temple%20prison%20September%201792&f=false Israel, J. (2014) Revolutionary Ideas, p. 267-277]\n* Loomis, S. (1964) Paris in the Terror. New York: Dorset Press. {{ISBN|0-88029-401-9}} [https://www.questia.com/read/71902509/historical-dictionary-of-the-french-revolution-1789-1799 online]\n* Scott, S.F. & B. Rothaus, eds. (1985) ''Historical Dictionary of the French Revolution 1789\u20131799''.  Vol. 2 pp.&nbsp;891\u201397. \n* Tulard, J. & J-F. Fayard and A. Fierro (1998) ''Histoire et Dictionnaire de la R\u00e9volution Fran\u00e7aise''. {{ISBN| 2-221-08850-6}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* [https://warwick.ac.uk/fac/arts/history/students/modules/comparative_revolutions/programme/frenchrev2/furet_terror.pdf F. Furet (1989) Terror. In: A critical dictionary of the French Revolution] \n* Hibbert, Christopher (1980) ''The Days of the French Revolution''. William Morrow, New York.\n* [[Schama, Simon]] (1992) ''[[Citizens: A Chronicle of the French Revolution]]'' pp.&nbsp;629\u201339.\n* [https://h-france.net/rude/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/TackettVol4.pdf Tackett, Timothy (2011) \"Rumor and Revolution: The Case of the September Massacres\", ''French History and Civilization'' Vol. 4, pp. 54\u201364.]\n\n===Eyewitnesses===\n* [https://books.google.nl/books?id=mPANAAAAQAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Sta\u00ebl+Robespierre&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi_v7nI96jeAhXJKVAKHT7lDzAQ6AEIRTAE#v=onepage&q=destined%20to%20be%20massacred&f=false Madame de Sta\u00ebl (1818) Considerations on the Principal Events of the French Revolution, Band 2, p. 68]\n* [https://books.google.nl/books?id=MeRBAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA26&dq=la+verite+du+evenements+de+2+septembre&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjHkMi2n6ffAhWDqaQKHXrwCYc4ChDoAQgvMAE#v=onepage&q=la%20verite%20du%20evenements%20de%202%20septembre&f=false La V\u00e9rit\u00e9 toute enti\u00e8re sur les vrais acteurs de 2. Septembre 1792 par Jean Claude Hippolyte M\u00e9h\u00e9e de la Touche]\n* [http://libx.bsu.edu/cdm/compoundobject/collection/FrnchRev/id/614/rec/8 Histoire de la conjugation de Maximilien Robespierre]\n* [https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k64357941/f1n312.pdf?download=1 Nicolas-Edme Restif de la Bretonne (1793) Les nuits de Paris, ou Le spectateur nocturne, p. 371-394]\n* [http://chnm.gmu.edu/revolution/d/393/ The September Massacres witnessed by Earl Gower, a British diplomat]\n\n===Fictional accounts===\n* [[Charles Dickens|Dickens, Charles]], ''[[A Tale of Two Cities]]'' (1859).\n* Henty, George Alfred, ''In the Reign of Terror''.\n* Neville, Katherine, ''The Eight'' (1988).\n\n===See also===\n* [[The Legislative Assembly and the fall of the French monarchy]]\n\n==External links==\n* [https://erenow.net/modern/a-peoples-history-of-the-french-revolution/8.php Eric Hazan (2012) A People's History of the French Revolution. June to August 1792. The journ\u00e9e of 20 June, the Brunswick Manifesto, the taking of the Tuileries, the end of the monarchy, the September massacres]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20041125082150/http://campus.northpark.edu/history/WEBChron/westeurope/SeptMassacres.html \"The September Massacres : 2\u20137 Sept. 1792\"] (archived link)\n* [http://www.english.ucsb.edu/faculty/ayliu/research/around-1800/FR/carlyle.html Thomas Carlyle on the September Massacres]\n* [http://www.carnavalet.paris.fr/sites/default/files/styles/oeuvre_zoom/public/40057-2.jpg?itok=YFGt9YOT Massacre de 2, 3, 4, 5 et 6 septembre (print)]\n* [https://archive.org/details/lamassacresdesep00lenouoft/page/n11 Les massacres de Septembre (1910) by Lenotre, G]\n\n{{French Revolution navbox}}\n\n{{coord missing|France}}\n\n[[Category:1792 events of the French Revolution]]\n[[Category:Anti-Catholicism in France]]\n[[Category:18th century in Paris]]\n[[Category:Massacres in France]]\n[[Category:Prison massacres]]\n[[Category:People killed in the French Revolution]]\n[[Category:Massacres committed by France]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2011}}\n[[File:1797 Jean Map of Paris and the Faubourgs, France - Geographicus - Paris-jean-1797.jpg|thumb|270px|Map of Paris and the Faubourgs (1797). The [[La Force prison]] was in [[Le Marais]] on Rue Pav\u00e9e, near [[Place des Vosges|Place des F\u00e9d\u00e9r\u00e9s]]. The [[Conciergerie]] was located on the westside of the [[\u00cele de la Cit\u00e9]], next to the [[Palais de Justice, Paris|Palais de Justice]].]] \n[[File:Massacre \u00e0 la Salp\u00eatri\u00e8re.jpg|thumb|270px|The [[Salp\u00eatri\u00e8re]] hospital where 35 women were killed.]]\n[[File:H\u00f4pital Royal de Bic\u00eatre, Paris; panoramic view with gardens Wellcome L0003004.jpg|thumb|270px|The royal hospital [[Bic\u00eatre]] where 150-170 men were killed.]]\n\nThe '''September Massacres''' were a series of killings of prisoners in Paris that occurred from 2\u20136 September 1792 during the [[French Revolution]].  They lasted from Sunday afternoon until Thursday evening. [[Charlotte Corday]] held [[Jean-Paul Marat]] responsible, but for [[Madame Roland]] it was [[Georges Danton]].<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=PaN4DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA97&lpg=PA97&dq=charlotte+corday+marat+responsible+september+massacre&source=bl&ots=egZw2jch2B&sig=ACfU3U3WvsIr1aaCoH2ohd6aXPJHcPTKww&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj02_C_vfPmAhXCYlAKHUyuAkcQ6AEwBnoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=charlotte%20corday%20marat%20responsible%20september%20massacre&f=false Watanabe-O'Kelly, H. (2018) From Viragos to Valkyries Transformations of the Heroic Warrior Woman in German literature from the Seventeenth to the Nineteenth Century. In: Tracing the Heroic Through Gender]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=fIZBE5JmbJUC&pg=PT98&hl=de&source=gbs_toc_r&cad=4#v=onepage&q=Massacre%20poisened&f=false The Giant of the French Revolution: Danton, A Life by David Lawday]</ref> Danton was also accused by the French historians [[Adolphe Thiers]], [[Alphonse Lamartine]], [[Jules Michelet]], [[Louis Blanc]] and [[Edgar Quinet]]. According to [[Albert Soboul]] there is no proof, however, that the massacres were organized by Danton or by anyone else, though it is certain that he did nothing to stop them.<ref>[https://www.britannica.com/biography/Georges-Danton/Dantons-Committee-of-Public-Safety Britannica.com]</ref> \n\nIt is estimated that around 1,100-1,600 people were murdered. The action was undertaken by 235<ref>[https://archive.org/details/histoiredesgiron02gran/page/312 <!-- quote=187. --> Adolphe Granier de Cassagnac (1860) Histoire Des Girondins Et Des Massacres de Septembre, Band 2, p. 29-30]</ref> ''[[F\u00e9d\u00e9r\u00e9]]s'', [[National Guard (France)|Guardsmen]] and [[Sansculottes]], with the support of [[National Gendarmerie|Gendarmes]], the latter were responsible for guarding the tribunals and prisons,<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=QTg_AAAAcAAJ&pg=PA417&lpg=PA417&dq=couvre-feu+28+aout+1792&source=bl&ots=_HF3YHDGtQ&sig=2-EsOuOC3t74zR8_vrGMdsqlSXo&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwipyJLx-Z7fAhWDCewKHaF-A-sQ6AEwDHoECAMQAQ#v=onepage&q=31%20AOUT&f=false Collection Compl\u00e8te des Lois, D\u00e9crets, Ordonnances, R\u00e9glements, p. 458]</ref> the [[Cordeliers]], the Insurrectional Commune and the [[Revolutionary sections of Paris]].<ref>P. Caron (1935), p. 107, 114</ref><ref>S. Schama, p. 611</ref><ref>[https://warwick.ac.uk/fac/arts/history/students/modules/comparative_revolutions/programme/frenchrev2/furet_terror.pdf F. Furet & M. Ozouf (1989) A Critical Dictionary of the French Revolution, p. 139]</ref><ref>Adolphe Granier de Cassagnac (1862?) Histoire des Girondins et des Massacres de Septembre, p. ?</ref> We will never know the identity of the \"septembriseurs\". But a large number of them were undoubtedly Parisian national guards and provincial federates who remained in the city since their arrival in July.<ref>[https://www.lhistoire.fr/septembre-1792-de-la-rumeur-au-massacre Septembre 1792 : de la rumeur au massacre by T. Tackett]</ref> By 6 September, half the prison population of Paris had been summarily executed. The exact number is not known; about 440-500 people had uncertain fates, including 200 Swiss soldiers.<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=DvlXDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT1&lpg=PT1&dq=Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric+Bluche,+Septembre+1792+:+logiques+d%27un+massacre&source=bl&ots=a1sr2GXf7z&sig=cvmJ82u26SEUyukTQEcyz0XJ0IM&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjwnIGQqbXeAhXNFsAKHZCoALUQ6AEwCHoECAEQAQ#v=onepage&q=Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric%20Bluche%2C%20Septembre%201792%20%3A%20logiques%20d'un%20massacre&f=false Septembre 1792 : logiques d'un massacre by Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Bluche (1986), p. ?]</ref><ref>[https://ia801409.us.archive.org/2/items/larvolution00madeuoft/larvolution00madeuoft.pdf L. Madelin, p. 256]</ref> However, the great majority (72%) of those killed were non-political prisoners - galley convicts, [[forgery|forgers]] of [[assignats]], common criminals, women, and children; 17% were Catholic priests.<ref>{{cite book|author=Gwynne Lewis|title=The French Revolution: Rethinking the Debate|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gNIHpeoORmQC&pg=PA38|year=2002|publisher=Routledge|page=38}}</ref><ref>Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Bluche (1986) Septembre 1792 : logiques d'un massacre, p. 235</ref> The Minister of Interior [[Jean-Marie Roland de la Plati\u00e8re|Roland]] accused the Commune of the atrocities. According to [[Georges Lefebvre]] the collective mentality is a [[sufficient]] explanation for the killing.<ref name=\"Georges Lefebvre 2001\">Georges Lefebvre, ''The French Revolution: From its Origins to 1793'' (2001) p.236</ref> For [[Timothy Tackett]] \"the obsession with a prison conspiracy, the desire for revenge, the fear of the advancing Prussians, the ambiguity over who was in control of a state that had always relied in the past on a centralized monarchy: all had come together in a volatile mixture of anger, fear, and uncertainty.\"<ref>[https://h-france.net/rude/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/TackettVol4.pdf Tackett, Timothy (2011) \"Rumor and Revolution: The Case of the September Massacres\", ''French History and Civilization'' Vol. 4, pp. 54\u201364.]</ref>\n\nThere was a fear that foreign and royalist armies would attack Paris and that the (Swiss) inmates of the city's prisons would be freed and join them. On 1 September [[National Legislative Assembly (France)|Legislative Assembly]] called for volunteers who gathered the next day on the [[Champs de Mars]].<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=QTg_AAAAcAAJ&pg=PA459&dq=1+Septembre+1792+paris&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwinyK-viejmAhWIPFAKHQ0GBU84FBDoAQhKMAQ#v=onepage&q=1%20Septembre%201792%20paris&f=false Collection Compl\u00e8te des Lois, D\u00e9crets, Ordonnances, R\u00e9glements, p. 459-460]</ref> On Sunday 2 September around one, [[Georges Danton|Danton]], a member of the provisional government, delivered a speech in the assembly: \u201cWe ask that any one refusing to give personal service or to furnish arms shall be punished with death\u201d.<ref>[http://www2.assemblee-nationale.fr/decouvrir-l-assemblee/histoire/grands-discours-parlementaires/danton-2-septembre-1792 Assembl\u00e9e Nationale]</ref> \u201cThe bell we are about to ring is not an alarm signal; it sounds the charge on the enemies of our country\". After applause he continued, \u201cTo conquer them we must dare, dare again, always dare, and France is saved!\u201d.<ref>[https://www.bartleby.com/268/7/20.html  The World\u2019s Famous Orations. Continental Europe (380\u20131906).  1906.]</ref><ref>[https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k54946638.texteImage Discours de Danton : Edition critique par Andr\u00e9 Fribourg, p. 172. Paris Au si\u00e9ge de la Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 1910.]</ref> His speech acted as a call for direct action among the citizens, as well as a strike against the external enemy.<ref>[https://www.lrb.co.uk/the-paper/v31/n15/hilary-mantel/he-roared [[Hillary Mantel]] in London Review of Books]</ref> <!--In reality Danton was probably speaking of boldness needed in fighting the war but some French citizens took it as boldness needed in fighting within France to those who were viewed as \u201ctraitors\u201d and killing occurred all over the streets.<ref>[http://westerncivguides.umwblogs.org/2011/09/25/jacobins-vs-girondins-during-the-french-revolution/]</ref>  -->  Many believe this speech was responsible for inciting the September Massacres.\n\nThe  massacre began around 2.30 in the middle of [[Saint-Germain-des-Pr\u00e9s#The French Revolution|Saint-Germain-des-Pr\u00e9s]]. Within the first 20 hours more than 1,000 prisoners were killed. The next morning on 3 September the <!--Assembly authorized employees to leave office and defend the country. The--> surveillance committees of the Commune, on which Marat now served, published a circular that called on provincial Patriots to defend Paris and asked that, before leaving their homes, they eliminate counter-revolutionaries. The secretary of the Commune, [[Jean-Lambert Tallien]] called on other cities to follow suit.<ref>F. Furet and M. Ozouf, eds. ''A Critical Dictionary of the French Revolution'' (1989), pp. 521\u201322</ref> The massacres were repeated in a few other French cities; in total 65-75 incidents were reported.<ref>P. Caron (1935) Les massacres de Septembre, p. 363-394. Part IV covers comparable events in provincial cities that transpired from July to October 1792.</ref><ref>P. McPhee (2016) Liberty or Death, p. 162</ref> \n\n==Background==\n===The Duke of Brunswick's manifesto=== \n\n[[File:Le Grand Ch\u00e2telet vu depuis la rue Saint-Denis, 1800.jpg|thumb|200px|The [[Grand Ch\u00e2telet]] from the north where about 220 people were killed.]]\n[[File:Porte Saint-Bernard Adam Perelle.jpg|thumb|200px|[[Ch\u00e2teau de la Tournelle|Saint-Bernard]] where 75 men (forgers?) convicted to the galley were killed.]]\n[[File:St firmin.jpg|thumb|200px|Saint Firmin in the Rue Saint Victor were 73 seminarians were killed.]]\n\nIn April 1792 France declared war on the [[Habsburg Monarchy]], prompting the [[War of the First Coalition]]. In July, an army under the [[Charles William Ferdinand, Duke of Brunswick-Wolfenb\u00fcttel|Duke of Brunswick]] and composed mostly of [[Kingdom of Prussia|Prussians]] joined the Austrian side and invaded France. As the army advanced, Paris went into a state of hysteria, especially after the Duke issued the \"[[Brunswick Manifesto]]\" on 25 July. His avowed aim was\n<blockquote>to put an end to the anarchy in the interior of France, to check the attacks upon the throne and the altar, to reestablish the legal power, to restore to the king the security and the liberty of which he is now deprived and to place him in a position to exercise once more the legitimate authority which belongs to him.<ref>{{cite book|author=Arno J. Mayer|title=The Furies: Violence and Terror in the French and Russian Revolutions|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gveBKGhmskAC&pg=PA554|year=2000|publisher=Princeton U.P.|page=554}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nThe Manifesto threatened the French population with instant punishment should it resist the Imperial and Prussian armies, or the reinstatement of the monarchy. The Manifesto was frequently described as unlawful and offensive to national sovereignty. Its authorship was frequently in doubt. Revolutionaries like Marat and H\u00e9bert suggested to concentrate on the internal enemy.<ref>[https://www.academia.edu/915802/_The_Myth_of_the_Foreign_Enemy_The_Brunswick_Manifesto_and_the_Radicalization_of_the_French_Revolution_French_History_25_no._2_2011_188-213?email_work_card=view-paper \"The Myth of the Foreign Enemy? The Brunswick Manifesto and the Radicalization of the French Revolution,\" French History 25, no. 2 (2011): 188-213 by Elisabeth Cross]</ref> On 3 August P\u00e9tion and 47 sections demanded the deposition of the king.\n\n===The insurrection of the Paris commune===\nOn the evening of 9 August 1792, a [[Jacobin]] insurrection overthrew the leadership of the Paris municipality, proclaiming a new [[Paris Commune (French Revolution)|revolutionary Commune]] headed by transitional authorities. The next day the insurrectionists [[10 August (French Revolution)|stormed the Tuileries Palace]]. King [[Louis XVI of France|Louis XVI]] was imprisoned with the royal family, and his authority as King was suspended by the [[National Legislative Assembly (France)|\nLegislative Assembly]]. The next day the royalist press was silenced. A provisional executive (Conseil ex\u00e9cutif) was named and busied itself with reorganizing or solving questions concerning the police, justice, the army, navy and paper money but actual power now rested with the new revolutionary Commune, whose strength resided in the mobilized and armed ''[[sans-culottes]]'', the lower classes of Paris, and ''[[f\u00e9d\u00e9r\u00e9s]]'', armed volunteers from the provinces that had arrived at the end of July. The 48 sections of Paris were equipped with munitions from the plundered arsenals in the days before the assault, substituting for the 60 National Guard battalions. Supported by a new armed force, the Commune dominated the Legislative Assembly and its decisions.<ref>Bergeron, Louis, ''Le Monde et son Histoire'', Paris, 1970, Volume VII, Chapter VII, p. 324</ref> The Commune pushed through several measures: universal suffrage was adopted, the civilian population was armed, all remnants of noble privileges were abolished and the [[Biens nationaux|properties]] of the ''[[\u00e9migr\u00e9s]]'' were sold. These events meant a change of direction from the political and constitutional perspective of the [[Girondists]] to a more social approach given by the Commune as expressed by [[Pierre-Joseph Cambon]]: \"To reject with more efficacy the defenders of despotism, we have to address the fortunes of the poor, we have to associate the Revolution with this multitude that possesses nothing, we have to convert the people to the cause.\"<ref>L. Bergeron (1970), p. 325.</ref>\n\nBesides these measures, the Commune engaged in a policy of political repression of all suspected counter-revolutionary activities. Beginning on 11 August, every Paris section named surveillance committees (Committees of Vigilance), which conducting searches and making arrests.<ref>[https://warwick.ac.uk/fac/arts/history/students/modules/comparative_revolutions/programme/frenchrev2/furet_terror.pdf F. Furet & M. Ozouf (1989) A Critical Dictionary of the French Revolution, p. 139]</ref> It was mostly these decentralized committees, rather than the Commune as a whole, which engaged in the repression of August and September 1792. Within a few days each section elected three commissioners to take seat in the insurrectionary Commune, chaired by [[Maximilien Robespierre]]. To ensure that there was some appropriate legal process for dealing with suspects accused of political crimes and treason, rather than arbitrary killing by local committees, a [[Revolutionary Tribunal|revolutionary tribunal]], with extraordinary powers to impose the death sentence without any [[appeal]]<ref>In 1815, a secretary of the Convention, writing under the pseudonyme ''Proussinale'', published some remarkable details about the procedure, [https://books.google.nl/books?id=IV8IAAAAQAAJ&pg=PP11&lpg=PP11&dq=proussinalle&source=bl&ots=wclT9Bbqol&sig=qjJTWyG0P6SnNlqImc5wnraDuvs&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiL3NGouZzfAhWFJ1AKHb4rB1YQ6AEwD3oECAQQAQ#v=onepage&q=robespierre&f=false Histoire secr\u00e8te du tribunal r\u00e9volutionnaire, par M. de Proussinalle, Band 1, p. 2-6]</ref>, was installed on 17 August.<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=y2vy9y9LDvwC&pg=PA277&lpg=PA277&dq=17+august+1792+tribunal+danton&source=bl&ots=M2HaPKgaIo&sig=xBzJDnu4p-C8u4mLOxoCnpK5cew&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiYh42u_5nfAhWosKQKHeE8CGU4ChDoATAHegQICBAB#v=onepage&q=17%20august%201792%20tribunal%20danton&f=false Press in the French Revolution, p. 277]</ref> Robespierre, who had proposed this measure, refused to preside over the tribunal, arguing that the same man ought not to be a denouncer, an accuser, and a judge.<ref name=\"Scurr\">{{cite book|author=Ruth Scurr|author-link=Ruth Scurr |title=Fatal Purity: Robespierre and the French Revolution|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CojtKDmS_ocC|date=17 April 2007|publisher=Henry Holt and Company|isbn=978-0-8050-8261-6}}</ref>{{rp|201}} \n\nAlready on 15 August four sections called for all priests and imprisoned suspects to be put to death before the volunteers departed. Robespierre proposed to erect a pyramid on [[Place Vend\u00f4me]] to remember the victims of 10 August. On 19 August the [[Civil Constitution of the Clergy#Jurors and non-jurors|nonjuring]] priests were ordered to leave the country within two weeks, which meant before 2 September 1792. (In Paris, all monasteries were closed and soon be in use as hospitals, etc. The remaining religious orders were banned by the law of 15 August.<ref>L. Bergeron, p. 326</ref>) [[Jean-Paul Marat|Marat]] left nothing in doubt when he urged \"good citizens to go to the Abbaye, to seize priests, and especially the officers of the Swiss guards and their accomplices and run a sword through them\".<ref>S. Schama, p. 630; L'Amie du peuple, no 680</ref> From 15 to 25 August, around 500 detentions were registered; some were sent to Orl\u00e9ans. Half the detentions were of nonjuring priests, but even priests who had sworn the required oath were caught in the wave.\n\n===Prussian advance and Paris reaction===\n\nOn Sunday, 26th August, news reached Paris that the Prussian army had [[Battle of Verdun (1792)|attacked the key fortress of Verdun]]. [[Jean-Marie Roland de la Plati\u00e8re|Roland]] proposed that the government should leave Paris, whereas Robespierre suggested in a letter to the sections of the Commune that they should defend liberty and equality and maintain their posts, and die if necessary.<ref>[[Jean Massin]] (1959) Robespierre, p. 133-134</ref> The Assembly decreed that all the non-juring priests had to leave Paris within 8 days and the country within two weeks.<ref>Le Moniteur universel, t. XIII, n\u00b0 241, du 28 a\u00f4ut, p. 540</ref>  In the evening, in the presence of 350,000 people, a funeral ceremony was held in the gardens of the Tuileries for those killed while [[Insurrection of 10 August 1792|storming the Tuileries]].<ref>[Le Moniteur universel, t. XIII, n\u00b0 244, du 31 a\u00f4ut, p. 572<]</ref> \n\nOn 28 August, the Assembly ordered a curfew for the next two days.<ref name=\"Massin\"/> On the behest of justice minister Danton, thirty commissioners from the sections were ordered to search in every suspect house for weapons, munition, swords, carriages and horses.<ref>S. Schama, p. 626</ref><ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=QTg_AAAAcAAJ&pg=PA417&lpg=PA417&dq=couvre-feu+28+aout+1792&source=bl&ots=_HF3YHDGtQ&sig=2-EsOuOC3t74zR8_vrGMdsqlSXo&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwipyJLx-Z7fAhWDCewKHaF-A-sQ6AEwDHoECAMQAQ#v=onepage&q=28%20AOUT&f=false Collection Compl\u00e8te des Lois, D\u00e9crets, Ordonnances, R\u00e9glements, p. 440]</ref> Before 2 September, between 520\u20131,000 people were taken into custody on the flimsiest warrants. The exact number of those arrested will never be known.<ref>S. Loomis, p. 77</ref> \n\nOn 29th August, the Prussians took Verdun, gaining a clear westward path to [[Paris]].<ref name=\"Parker2008\">{{Cite book|last=Parker |first=Geoffrey |title=The Cambridge Illustrated History of Warfare |year=2008 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |location=New York |isbn=978-0-521-73806-4 |page=195 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yqNj5BlEMtcC&pg=PA195|accessdate=22 January 2012 }}</ref> When this news arrived two days later it escalated the sense of panic. On 1 September the citizens were told to prepare themselves for the defense of the country and gather immediately on the sound of the tocsin.<ref>Le Moniteur universel, t. XIII, n\u00b0 248, du 5 septembre, p. 590</ref> Their imminent departure from the capital provoked further concern about the crowded prisons, now full of counter-revolutionary suspects who might threaten a city deprived of so many of its defenders.<ref>Cobb, R. & C. Jones (1988) The French Revolution. Voices from a momentous epoch 1789-1795, p. 159</ref>  Marat called for a \"new blood-letting\", larger than the one on 10 August. <!--He stopped publishing [[L'Ami du peuple]] for a few weeks. For a while he published posters printed in the basement of the [[Cordeliers Convent]].<ref>Gottschalk, Louis R. (1927, reissued 1966). Jean-Paul Marat: A Study in Radicalism, Benjamin Bloom, p. 97.</ref>) The four printing press he used came from the Tuileries.--> The British ambassador reported:\n<blockquote>A party at the instigation of someone or other declared they would not quit Paris, as long as the prisons were filled with Traitors (for they called those so, that were confined in the different Prisons and Churches), who might in the absence of such a number of Citizens rise and not only effect the release of His Majesty, but make an entire counterrevolution.<ref>Oscar Browning, ed., ''The Despatches of Earl Gower'' (Cambridge University Press, 1885), 213\u201316, 219\u201321, 223\u201328.</ref></blockquote><!--according to [[Louis-Marie Prudhomme]] \"Marat proposed to set the prisons on fire, but it was pointed out to him that the neighboring houses would be endangered; someone else advised flooding them. Billaud-Varennes proposed butchering the prisoners. [[Jean-Lambert Tallien]], the Commune's secretary-general, showed disgust at the discussion, but did not have the courage to oppose it.\"{{cn|date=December 2019}} [[Marquis de Condorcet|Condorcet]] argued that any \"enemies of the people\" belonged to the Nation and that prisoners ought not be judged by members of the Commune, but by the Nation, earning him the enmity of Marat and Robespierre.{{cn|date=December 2019}} Marat was also furious at Roland, who had refused him a financial subsidy according to [[Louis Madelin]].{{cn|date=December 2019}}-->\n\nThroughout August, the Legislative Asssembly, which had been greatly diminished as more than half of the deputies had fled since the storming of the Tuileries, had acquiesced to the activities of the Commune and its sections. On 30 August, the Girondins Roland and [[Marguerite-\u00c9lie Guadet]] tried to suppress the influence of the Commune, accused of exercising unlawful power. The Assembly, tired of the pressures, declared the Commune illegal and suggested the organization of communal elections and a doubling of the number of seats.<ref name=\"Israel267\">J. Israel (2014), ''Revolutionary Ideas'', p. 267-268.</ref><ref name=\"Massin\">J. Massin (1959), ''Robespierre'', p. 132.</ref> However, the Assembly cancelled the decree the next day at the request of [[Jacques-Alexis Thuriot de la Rosi\u00e8re|Jacques-Alexis Thuriot]]. The balance of power was disrupted and the conflict between the Girondins and the Montagnards would influence the progress of the French Revolution.<ref name=\"Israel267\"/>\n\nOn 1 September, the gates of the city, closed the days before, were opened on the orders of P\u00e9tion, providing an opportunity for suspects to flee the capital. According to [[Louis-Marie Prudhomme]] people still profited from the opportunity on Sunday morning 2 September.<ref>L. Bluche, p. 258</ref> The Assembly decreed to arm the volunteers; a third would stay in Paris and defend the city with pikes, the others were meant for the frontier and the trenches. It further decreed that traitors who refused to participate in the defense or hand over their arms deserved death.<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=QTg_AAAAcAAJ&pg=PA459&dq=1+Septembre+1792+paris&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwinyK-viejmAhWIPFAKHQ0GBU84FBDoAQhKMAQ#v=onepage&q=1%20Septembre%201792%20paris&f=false Collection Compl\u00e8te des Lois, D\u00e9crets, Ordonnances, R\u00e9glements, p. 459-460]</ref> The sections, gathered in the townhall, decided to remain in Paris; Marat proposed to have Roland and his fellow [[Girondists|Girondist]] Brissot arrested.<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=DvlXDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=logiques+d%27un+massacre&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjtvPio06PfAhULC-wKHa30BdwQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=insens\u00e9&f=false Septembre 1792: logiques d'un massacre by Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Bluche]</ref> <!--At noon--> The Commune ordered the gates closed and an alarm gun fired. After the tocsin was rung around 2 o'clock 60,000 men enrolled for the defense of the country on the Champs de Mars. <!--It seems 10,000 were without weapons.-->\n\n==Massacres==\n[[File:Massacres des 2, 3, 4, 5 et 6 septembre 1792.jpg|thumb|200px|[[Prison de l'Abbaye]] where between 160-220 people were killed in three days. It was located between Rue de Bussi and Rue du Four (E40), with the entrance on Rue Sainte-Marguerite, today 133, [[Boulevard Saint-Germain]].]]\n[[File:Stanislas-marie-maillard.jpg|thumb|200px|[[Stanislas-Marie Maillard]] ]]\n[[File:Massacre des Carmes-Bilcocq-IMG 2416.JPG|thumb|200px|115 priests were killed in the [[Carmes prison]]. ''Le massacre des Carmes'' by Marie-Marc-Antoine Bilcocq, (1820). [[Mus\u00e9e de la R\u00e9volution fran\u00e7aise]].]]\n[[File:Conciergerie in 1790.jpg|thumb|200px|[[Conciergerie]] where 250-3,0 people were killed.]]\n[[File:Massacre ch\u00e2telet 1792.jpg|thumb|200px|Mass killing of more than 200 prisoners in the Ch\u00e2telet on 3 September]] \n\nThe first massacre began in [[quartier Latin]] around 2.30 on Sunday afternoon when 24 [[Civil Constitution of the Clergy#Jurors and non-jurors|non-juring priest]]s were being transported to the [[prison de l'Abbaye]] near the [[Abbey of Saint-Germain-des-Pr\u00e9s#Former configuration|Abbey of Saint-Germain-des-Pr\u00e9s]], after being interrogated by [[Billaud-Varenne]] in the townhall. One of the carriages, escorted by F\u00e9d\u00e9r\u00e9s, was attacked after an incident.<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=yDIEAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA268&lpg=PA268&dq=insurrection+french+revolution&source=bl&ots=53T3ZQ6WRN&sig=bkjxrkuajhSUrkdDo5s9yYDBOpU&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj2v6qpwdDdAhWFLewKHeZbAecQ6AEwDXoECAAQAQ#v=onepage&q=Lamballe&f=false The history of the French revolution, tr. with notes by Marie Joseph L. Adolphe Thiers, p. 144]</ref> The F\u00e9d\u00e9r\u00e9s killed three men in the middle of the street, before the procession arrived at the prison. Eighteen arrested were taken inside. They then mutilated the bodies, \"with circumstances of barbarity too shocking to describe\" according to the British diplomatic dispatch. One of their victims was the former Minister of Foreign Affairs [[Armand Marc, comte de Montmorin]]. [[Roch-Ambroise Cucurron Sicard]] was recognized as beneficent priest and released. \n\nIn the late afternoon 115 priests in the [[Carmes prison|former convent of Carmelites]], detained with the message they would be deported to [[French Guiana]], were massacred in the courtyard with axes, spikes, swords and pistols by people (with a strong [[patois]] accent). They forced the priests one by one to take the oath on the [[Civil Constitution of the Clergy]], and \"swear to be faithful to the nation and to maintain liberty and equality or die defending it\".<ref>F. Bluche, p. 219</ref>  The priests hid in the choir and behind the altar. Several tried to escape by climbing in the trees and over the walls and escaped through Rue Cassette.<ref>[https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k65832786.texte Image Les Massacres du 2 septembre 1792 \u00e0 la prison des Carmes \u00e0 Paris, p. ?]</ref><ref>S. Loomis, p. 79</ref> <!--When the L\u00e9gislative became aware of what happened six or seven commissioners were send out to check the other prisons. --> \n\nAround five a group of 200 \"Septembriseurs\" came to the house of Roland on [[Place Dauphine]] to arrest him, but as he was at the Ministry they went there. Between seven and eight o'clock in the evening the group of F\u00e9d\u00e9r\u00e9s, etc. was back at the Abbaye prison. (The Abbaye prison was located in what is now the [[Boulevard Saint-Germain]] just west of the current Passage de la Petite Boucherie.) The door was closed, but the bloody work was resumed after an intense discussion with Manuel, the procurator, on people's justice and failing judges.<ref>F. Bluche, p. 56-60</ref> He belonged to a deputation sent by the Commune to ask for compassion.<ref>L. Blanc (1855) Histoire de la R\u00e9volution Fran\u00e7aise, vol VII, p. 163</ref> They were insulted and escaped with their lives.<ref>Oscar Browning, ed., ''The Despatches of [[George Leveson-Gower, 1st Duke of Sutherland|Earl Gower]]'' (Cambridge University Press, 1885), 213\u201316, 219\u201321, 223\u201328.</ref> A tribunal composed of twelve people, presided by Stanislas-Marie Maillard, started the interrogating by asking the prisoner why he was arrested. A lie was fatal.<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=fAMxAQAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=L.+Blanc+(1855)+Histoire+de+la+R\u00e9volution+Fran\u00e7aise,+vol+VII&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjbpLmghJPfAhWKmbQKHXS-BFMQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=L.%20Blanc%20(1855)%20Histoire%20de%20la%20R\u00e9volution%20Fran\u00e7aise%2C%20vol%20VII&f=false L. Blanc (1855) Histoire de la R\u00e9volution Fran\u00e7aise, vol VII, p. 165]</ref> <!-- 135 Swiss inmates were killed, 27 were transferred, 86 were set free, and 36 had uncertain fates.<ref>Leborgne, Dominique, ''Saint-Germain-des-Pr\u00e9s et son faubourg'', p. 40, \u00c9ditions Parigramme, Paris, 2005, {{ISBN|2-84096-189-X}}</ref> According to [[George Long (scholar)|George Long]] 122 died, 43 people were released.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/franceanditsrev00longgoog/page/n175 <!-- pg=161 quote= Robespierre . --> France and Its Revolutions: A Pictorial History 1789-1848 by George Long, p. 199-202]</ref>--> \n\nIn the early evening groups broke into another Paris prison, the [[Conciergerie]]. According to Prudhomme people sat on the stairs of the Palace of Justice watching the butchery in the courtyard.<ref>F. Bluche, p. 260</ref> Not far away [[Nicolas-Edme Restif de la Bretonne|Restif de la Bretonne]] saw the bodies piled high on [[Pont Notre-Dame|Pont au Change]] in front of the [[Grand Ch\u00e2telet|Ch\u00e2telet]]. The corpses were thrown in the river. He recorded the atrocities he witnessed in ''Les Nuits de Paris'' (1794).<ref>[http://chnm.gmu.edu/revolution/d/392/ The September Massacres witnessed by Restif de la Bretonne]</ref> Late that night they went to [[Ch\u00e2teau de la Tournelle|Tour Saint-Bernard]] where the forgers of assignats were jailed. The pattern of semi-formal executions followed by the popular tribunals was for condemned prisoners to be ordered \"transferred\" or even \"released\" and then taken into the prison courtyards where they would be cut down. \n\nBefore midnight the [[seminary]] Saint Firmin was visited by just four men, who killed all the [[seminarian]]s. At 2.30 in the morning the Assembly was informed that most of the prisons were empty. <!--According to Tallien all prisoners involved in the events of 10 August or producing false assignats were killed.<ref>Le Moniteur universel, t. XIII, n\u00b0 248, du 4 septembre, p. 603</ref>--> The next morning the Assembly was still involved with the defense of the city; [[Marie-Jean H\u00e9rault de S\u00e9chelles|H\u00e9rault de S\u00e9chelles]] presided. It decided the other prisoners had to wait for their trial because of a temporary lack of judges.<ref>Le Moniteur universel, t. XIII, n\u00b0 248, du 5 septembre, p. 607</ref> \n\nAround 4 in the afternoon [[Madame de Sta\u00ebl]], as ambassadress of Sweden, who lived in [[Rue du Bac]] near Champ de Mars, tried to flee through crowded streets but her carriage was stopped and the crowd forced her to go to the [[H\u00f4tel de Ville, Paris|Paris town hall]], where [[Robespierre]] presided.<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=mPANAAAAQAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Sta\u00ebl+Robespierre&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi_v7nI96jeAhXJKVAKHT7lDzAQ6AEIRTAE#v=onepage&q=Sta\u00ebl%20Robespierre&f=false Considerations on the Principal Events of the French Revolution, Band 2, p. 75]</ref> Late in the evening, she was conveyed home, escorted by the [[public procurator|procurator]] [[Louis Pierre Manuel]]. The next day the secretary-general to the [[Paris Commune (French Revolution)|Commune of Paris]], Tallien, arrived with a passport and accompanied her to the [[Barricade|barrier]].<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=r2wBAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA341&lpg=PA341&dq=Manuel+germaine+de+stael&source=bl&ots=ccvAqmorAJ&sig=63s5MOtCsWb34fkom7anFCovO78&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwijiLrX6YXdAhXQ6aQKHYaWBEkQ6AEwEHoECAAQAQ#v=onepage&q=Manuel%20germaine%20de%20stael&f=false A New Dictionary of the French Revolution by Richard Ballard, p. 341]</ref>\n\nOn Monday morning nine o'clock, [[Billaud-Varenne]] came to the Abbaye prison and declared that the murderers should stop stealing and would get paid by the Commune. [[Bic\u00eatre]] (for men and boys) was visited twice that day after a rumor there were thousands of rifles stored. They brought seven cannons with them. The killing went on until the next day. At dawn [[H\u00f4pital de la Salp\u00eatri\u00e8re|Salp\u00eatri\u00e8re]] (for women and girls) was visited.<ref>F. Bluche, p. 193</ref> where prostitutes seem to have been released and young girls raped.<ref>https://www.tombes-sepultures.com/crbst_2169.html#anchor-Massacres</ref> On Tuesday afternoon the killing stopped finally in the Abbey. Police commissioners [[:fr:\u00c9tienne-Jean Panis]] and [[Antoine Louis Fran\u00e7ois Sergent dit Sergent-Marceau|Sergent-Marceau]] gave orders to wash away all the blood from the stairs and the courtyard, to spread straw, to count the corpses and to dispose of them on carts to avoid infections.<ref>L. Blanc, p. 182</ref> A contract was signed with the grave digger of the nearby [[\u00c9glise Saint-Sulpice, Paris]], who also had to purchase [[quicklime]].  On 5 September, the day of the election, it was perfectly quiet in Paris according [[Le Moniteur Universel]].<ref>Le Moniteur universel, t. XIII, n\u00b0 248, du 5 septembre, p. 613</ref> There were still 80 prisoners in \"La Force\". On 6 September the killing finally stopped.<ref>Le Moniteur universel, t. XIII, n\u00b0 251, du 7 septembre, p. 621</ref><ref>F. Bluche, p. 72, 193</ref> The next day the gates were opened, but it was impossible to travel to another d\u00e9partment without a passport.<ref>Le Moniteur universel, t. XIII, n\u00b0 248, du 7 septembre, p. 629</ref>\n\n===Contemporary reports===\n[[File:LaForcePrisonParis.jpg|thumb|200px|[[La Force prison]] where about 165 people were killed in 48 hours.]]\n\nAccording to Galart de Montjoie, a lawyer and a royalist, in those days everyone believed the F\u00e9d\u00e9r\u00e9s from Marseille, Avignon and Brest were involved in the killing.<ref>[http://libx.bsu.edu/cdm/compoundobject/collection/FrnchRev/id/614/rec/8 Histoire de la conjuration de Robespierre, p. 81. Paris, les marchands de nouveaut\u00e9s, 1795 ; Chez Maret, an IV(1796).]</ref><ref>F. Bluche, p. 233</ref><ref>[https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k367704/f1n650.pdf?download=1 L.M. Ternaux (1863) Histoire de la Terreur, 1792-1794, Tome III, p. 126, 224]</ref> About 800-1000 were staying in barrack, but moved supposedly to where events would take place. <!--During the storming of the Tuileries the F\u00e9d\u00e9res were in the front.<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=dD8XcGgMd_QC&dq=robespierre%20d%C3%A9fenseur%20de%20la%20constitution&hl=de&pg=PA572#v=onepage&q=marseillais&f=false Le D\u00e9fenseur de la Constitution, par Maximilien Robespierre, p. 571]</ref> It is not exactly known how many of them were killed; according to [[Axel von Fersen the Younger|Axel Fersen]] 600,<ref>Cobb, R. & C. Jones (1988) The French Revolution. Voices from a momentous epoch 1789-1795, p. 152-153</ref> according to Robespierre only hundred men.<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=dD8XcGgMd_QC&dq=robespierre%20d%C3%A9fenseur%20de%20la%20constitution&hl=de&pg=PA572#v=onepage&q=marseillais&f=falseLe D\u00e9fenseur de la Constitution, par Maximilien Robespierre, p 572]</ref>--> It seems around 300 F\u00e9d\u00e9r\u00e9s from Brest and 500 from Marseille were then lodged in [[Cordeliers Convent]].<ref>Hampson, Norman (1978) Danton (New York: Basil Blackwell), pp. 71\u201372.</ref><ref>S. Schama, p. 605, 611</ref><ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=iSMVAAAAQAAJ&printsec=frontcover&hl=de&source=gbs_atb#v=snippet&q=assignat&f=false Oeuvres, Band 2 von Maximilien Robespierre, p. 118] [https://books.google.nl/books?id=q2NSAAAAcAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Louis+Blanc+1855+Histoire&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiG6PKU6tveAhUPYVAKHfWbA5sQ6AEIMTAB#v=onepage&q&f=false L. Blanc (1855) Histoire de la R\u00e9volution Fran\u00e7aise. Vol. VII, p. 29]</ref> Servan planned to give them military training before using them to supplement the army at the front.\n\n{{quote|The fact is that the reports of conspiracies in the prisons, however improbable, and the constant propaganda about the people\u2019s will and the people\u2019s anger, held everyone in a sort of stupor and gave the impression that this infamous performance was the work of the populace, whereas in reality there were not above 200 criminals.<ref>The memoirs of Madame Roland, p. ? (London: Barrie & Jenkins, translated by Evelyn Shuckburgh (1989)</ref><ref>[http://libx.bsu.edu/cdm/compoundobject/collection/FrnchRev/id/614/rec/8 Histire de la conjugation de Maximilien Robespierre], p. 81</ref>}}\n\n{{quote|Though it is an ascertained fact that the perpetrators of the atrocious murders were but a few; yet it is not so clear that this work was not connived at, or consented to, by a much greater number, and those perhaps in authority; for otherwise, two or three companies of the town guard would have been sufficient to disperse those who were employed on the occasion.<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=MN-vXtoOXokC&printsec=frontcover&dq=perry+historical+sketch+French+revolution&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwil1-Lw8bLfAhUDJ1AKHR2VB7AQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=September&f=false Sampson Perry (1796) An Historical Sketch of the French Revolution: Commencing with Its predisposing causes, and carried on to the acceptation of the Constitution in 1795. Vol II, p. 230]</ref>}}\n\n{{quote|Perry describes the restoration of order after the events, giving the impression that the massacres may even have had a [[cathartic]] effect. He also suggests that France was plagued by fewer foreign enemies afterwards. What emerges therefore from Perry\u2019s report is a view that, if massacres did take place, they occurred not out of spontaneous popular madness but because of comprehensible grievances.<ref>[https://tel.archives-ouvertes.fr/tel-00797967/document Rachel Rogers (2012) Vectors of Revolution : The British Radical Community in Early Republican Paris, 1792-1794, p. 376. Universit\u00e9 Toulouse le Mirail]</ref>}} According to [[Adolphe Thiers]], [[George Long (scholar)|George Long]] and [[Stanley Loomis]] not an outburst of passion, but coldly and carefully organized.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/franceanditsrev00longgoog/page/n175 <!-- pg=161 quote= Robespierre . --> France and Its Revolutions: A Pictorial History 1789-1848 by George Long, p. 206-207]</ref><ref>S. Loomis, p. 74, 81, 96, 143, 207</ref>\n\n{{quote|Rather than being proof of the unprecedented depravity of an entire population, the prison massacres were the explicable result of both the \u201cwrath and fury\u201d of the victims of 10th August and the machinations of the Paris Commune, who gave their tacit consent to the killings.<ref>[[Helen Maria Williams]]\u2019 [[Letters Written in France|Letters from France]] (1792-93), Letter IV, p. 191</ref> Those targeted in the attacks had not been imprisoned unjustly, but had been suspected of having aided the court in its negotiations with foreign princes. In a similar way to Perry, Williams emphasizes the understandable impatience of the people, who had been kept waiting too long for justice after the August Days, when husbands, brothers and fathers had been killed.<ref>[https://tel.archives-ouvertes.fr/tel-00797967/document Rachel Rogers (2012) Vectors of Revolution : The British Radical Community in Early Republican Paris, 1792-1794, p. 402. Universit\u00e9 Toulouse le Mirail]</ref>}}\n\n===Numbers===\n[[File:MassacrePrincessLamballe.jpg|thumb|200px|A propaganda engraving of the September Massacres showing the killing of Priests; nuns and Princess de Lamballe]]\n[[File:Death-of-the-Princess-De-Lamballe-by-Leon-Maxime-Faivre.jpg|thumb|200px|L\u00e9on-Maxime Faivre (1908) Death of the Princess de Lamballe]]\n\nAccording to [[Pierre Caron (historian)|Pierre Caron]] there were almost 2,800 prisoners in early September. Between 1,250-1,450 prisoners were condemned and executed. According to Caron and Bluche 70% of the victims were killed in a 20-hour interval.<ref>F. Bluche, p. 192</ref> Among the victims were 223 [[:wikt:nonjuror|nonjuring]] Catholic priests and (arch)bishops who refused to submit to the [[Civil Constitution of the Clergy]], 81 [[Swiss guards]], and 40-80 political suspects, mostly royalists, aristocrats and some former judges and ministers<ref>P. Caron (1935) Les Massacres de Septembre, p. 94-99; 101-102</ref> including the queen's best friend, the [[Princess Marie Louise of Savoy|''Princesse de Lamballe'']], the only political victim in \"La petite Force\".<ref>[https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k40941v/f4.image The history of the French revolution, tr. with notes by Marie Joseph L. Adolphe Thiers]</ref>\n\nThe lives of about 1,250-1,600 prisoners brought before the people's courts were saved.<ref>P. Caron, p. 99</ref> In a few cases people were acclaimed as \"patriots\" by Robespierre, Tallien, Desmoulins and Danton.<ref>M. J. Sydenham ''The French Revolution'', B.T. Batsford Ltd, 1965, p. 121</ref><ref>L. Michelet, tome IV, p. 121</ref> Several prisoners for debts or alimony were released by Manuel or by the police before 2 September.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/histoiredesgiron02gran/page/312 <!-- quote=187. --> Adolphe Granier de Cassagnac (1860) Histoire Des Girondins Et Des Massacres de Septembre, Band 2, p. 34-35, 44]</ref> [[Louise-\u00c9lisabeth de Cro\u00ff de Tourzel]] was released from [[Port-Royal Abbey, Paris]] on order of the Commune. \n\nA total of nine prisons were violently entered during the five days of the massacres before the killings concluded on the night of 6\u20137 September; four were not visited ([[Sainte-P\u00e9lagie Prison]], [[Prison Saint-Lazare]], [[Square du Temple|Tour du Temple]] and palais Bourbon). About 700 surviving Swiss soldiers, locked up in [[Palais Bourbon]], marched to the townhall to take the oath and joined the volunteers.<ref>Le Moniteur universel, t. XIII, n\u00b0 251, du 7 septembre, p. 621</ref><ref>[https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k367704/f1n650.pdf?download=1 L.M. Ternaux (1863) Histoire de la Terreur, 1792-1794, d'apr\u00e8s des documents authentiques et in\u00e9dits. Tome III, p. 10, 298]</ref> After initially indiscriminate slayings, ad hoc popular tribunals were set up to distinguish between \"enemies of the people\" and those who were innocent, or at least were not perceived as counter-revolutionary threats. In spite of this attempted sifting, an estimated three-quarters of the 1,250\u20131,450 killed were not counter-revolutionaries or \"villains\", but included all the galley convicts, [[Forgery|forgers]] of [[assignats]], 37 women (including the Princess de Lamballe and the book-seller Marie Gredeler, who was accused of murder) and 66 children.<ref>P. Caron (1935) Les Massacres de Septembre, p. 95</ref><ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=NEosW4-twr4C&pg=PA110&lpg=PA110&dq=Marie+Gredeler+1792&source=bl&ots=RNBaUlUhjq&sig=EL7B2Cuh9Bu6tTHQv76xXAcQlYg&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjxhNuZjd3fAhWMa1AKHV2BA6kQ6AEwAnoECAEQAQ#v=onepage&q=Marie%20Gredeler%201792&f=false Demonic: How the Liberal Mob Is Endangering America by Ann Coulter, p. 110]</ref> Some priests and women were of age, about prostitutes or insane not much is known.<ref>Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Bluche (1986) Septembre 1792 : logiques d'un massacre, p. 235</ref>\n\nIn ''Paris in the Terror'', [[Stanley Loomis]] reports that during the massacre at the prison-hospital of [[Bic\u00eatre]], 33 boys aged between 12 and 18 were murdered by a group of 1,500-2,000 people.<ref>S. Loomis, p. 83</ref><ref>F. Bluche, p. 70</ref><ref>L.M. Ternaux, p. 295-296</ref> Mayor P\u00e9tion did not have much influence discussing [[Humanity (virtue)|humanity]] with them.<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=3gpBAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA346&lpg=PA346&dq=salpetriere+1792+septembre&source=bl&ots=Tcde_IezVW&sig=ACfU3U3GfJYAqoLuQFaakTNUfVDaMow5Ow&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiH6fnpupTnAhWHL1AKHeKYBYI4ChDoATADegQIBRAB#v=onepage&q=salpetriere%201792%20septembre&f=false M\u00e9moires sur les journ\u00e9es de septembre, 1792, p. 348 by Fran\u00e7ois de Jourgniac Saint-M\u00e9ard, Paysac Fars marquise de Fausse-Lendry, Sicard (M. l'abb\u00e9, Roch Ambroise Cucurron), Antoine Gabriel Aim\u00e9 Jourdan]</ref> Loomis also reported that afterwards \"girls as young as ten\" were murdered in [[Salp\u00eatri\u00e8re]] institution for women, mentally insane and prostitutes.<ref>{{Cite book| last =Loomis| first =Stanley|authorlink= Stanley Loomis |title =Paris in the Terror| publisher=Dorset Press| year =1964| location =New York| isbn=0-88029-401-9 }}</ref> The number of victims is exactly known: 35 women, including 23 underaged.<ref>F. Bluche, p. 454</ref>\n\n==Killings outside Paris==\nOn 3 September the <!--Assembly authorized employees to leave office and defend the country. The--> surveillance committees of the Commune, on which Marat now served, published a circular that called on provincial Patriots to defend Paris and asked that, before leaving their homes, they eliminate counter-revolutionaries. Marat advised the entire nation \"to adopt this necessary measure\".<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=9lWNCwAAQBAJ&pg=PR14-IA13&lpg=PR14-IA13&dq=the+entire+nation...+will+hasten+to+adopt+this+necessary+measure+French+revolution&source=bl&ots=9mhX7yi_YI&sig=YKfJVFVxpNjGJg9C-rIHm6aGCXQ&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjq7NGZobjeAhXH_aQKHXzQB_cQ6AEwA3oECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=the%20entire%20nation...%20will%20hasten%20to%20adopt%20this%20necessary%20measure%20French%20revolution&f=false The French Revolution: From Enlightenment to Tyranny by Ian Davidson]</ref>  \n\nA circular letter was sent to regional authorities by [[Fran\u00e7ois Louis Michel Chemin Deforgues|Deforgues]], an assistant of Danton, and [[Tallien]], the secretary of the Paris Commune, advising that \"ferocious conspirators detained in the prisons had been put to death by the people\".<ref>{{cite book |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=q9B-AAAAIAAJ&pg=RA2-PA725 |title=Charles Knight's Popular History of England |chapter=The French Revolution |page=725}} in {{cite book |last=Beale |first=Joseph H. |title=Gay's Standard History of the World's Great Nations |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=q9B-AAAAIAAJ |accessdate=31 August 2018 |volume=1 |year=1884 |publisher=W. Gay and Company}}</ref><ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=pm89AAAAYAAJ&pg=PA993&lpg=PA993&dq=tallien+september+massacres&source=bl&ots=a5atwqaCrb&sig=q_VBuzE4MmcylpezCUz-r1yrSl0&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjqhsf7kZPfAhVCK1AKHRjOAHQ4ChDoATANegQICRAB#v=onepage&q=tallien%20september%20massacres&f=false A general biographical dictionary: containing a summary ..., p. 993 by John Gorton]</ref><ref>[http://www.nndb.com/people/405/000098111/ Jean-Lambert Tallien]</ref> \n\nThe Girondins afterwards made much of this circular, but there is no evidence that it had any influence. As before, murders in the provinces continued: the blood-letting did not cease until the countryside was [[purged]]. <!--According to [[Georges Lefebvre]] the collective mentality is sufficient explanation for the killing.<ref name=\"Georges Lefebvre 2001\">Georges Lefebvre, ''The French Revolution: From its Origins to 1793'' (2001) p. 236</ref>--> Smaller-scale executions took place in Reims, [[Meaux]], and Lyon on 2, 4 and 9 September. <!--There were 75 separate incidents in 32 of France's 83 [[Departments of France|d\u00e9partments]].--> Most notable was the killing of 44 political prisoners near [[Ch\u00e2teau de Versailles]] transported from the High Court in Orl\u00e9ans back to Paris, the [[9 September massacres]].<ref>P. McPhee (2016) Liberty or Death, p. 162</ref> The next day Brissot wrote in \"Le Patriote fran\u00e7ais\", his newspaper: \"No doubt you will be told that it is a vengeance of the people; it will be a slander. The people were not involved in this event.\"<ref>F. Bluche, p. 256</ref>\n\n==Official role==\n\nAccording to [[Timothy Tackett]]:  \"For a period of some 48 hours between the 29th and the 31st of August the whole of Paris was systematically searched by the national guard for lurking conspirators and hidden arms.<ref>\"T. Tackett, p. 63</ref> By that time section assemblies were already passing motions demanding \"the death of conspirators before the departure of citizens\".<ref>S. Schama, p. 631</ref> \n\nOn 31 August the Committee of Vigilance was created with Panis and Sergent-Marceau. According to [[Madame de Sta\u00ebl]] on 31 August \"it was already known, that only those who were destined to be massacred were sent to that prison [of the Abbey].\"<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=mPANAAAAQAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Sta\u00ebl+Robespierre&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi_v7nI96jeAhXJKVAKHT7lDzAQ6AEIRTAE#v=onepage&q=destined%20to%20be%20massacred&f=false Considerations on the Principal Events of the French Revolution, Band 2, p. 68-70]</ref> \n\nOn 1 September the Commune declared a state of emergency by decreeing that on the following day the tocsin should be rung, all able-bodied citizens convened in the Champ de Mars.<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=QTg_AAAAcAAJ&pg=PA459&dq=1+Septembre+1792+paris&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwinyK-viejmAhWIPFAKHQ0GBU84FBDoAQhKMAQ#v=onepage&q=1%20Septembre%201792%20paris&f=false Collection Compl\u00e8te des Lois, D\u00e9crets, Ordonnances, R\u00e9glements, p. 459-460]</ref><!--The next day a decree passed in the Assembly to arm those 60,000 men and traitors who refused to participate in the defence or hand over their arms deserved death.<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=QTg_AAAAcAAJ&pg=PA459&dq=1+Septembre+1792+paris&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwinyK-viejmAhWIPFAKHQ0GBU84FBDoAQhKMAQ#v=onepage&q=1%20Septembre%201792%20paris&f=false Collection Compl\u00e8te des Lois, D\u00e9crets, Ordonnances, R\u00e9glements, p. 459-460]</ref>-->\nOn Sunday 2 September the [[1792 French National Convention election]] started. Robespierre publicly accused [[Brissot]] and the [[Brissotins]] of plotting with the Duke of Brunswick.<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=grUD3hWUc0AC&pg=PA56&lpg=PA56&dq=robespierre+september+massacres&source=bl&ots=zba6lKhLEu&sig=qm5IHGeu4dSUud_FDRRLKBF1N3o&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjplfTdz6PeAhXL_KQKHUASB_YQ6AEwDHoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=robespierre%20september%20massacres&f=false Robespierre by John Hardman, p. 56-57]</ref> Marat was appointed as one of the six additional members of the Committee of Vigilance, but without the approval of the Executive Council.<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=UV5WAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA585&lpg=PA585&dq=comit%C3%A9+de+surveillance+Marat+1792&source=bl&ots=KWgyQgUb0B&sig=ACfU3U16Vw5sfg6XF8l0mbadjALR1xDxrg&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj2h6fh4uLmAhWFGuwKHZ0iBd8Q6AEwAXoECAsQAQ#v=onepage&q=comit%C3%A9%20de%20surveillance%20Marat%201792&f=false Action politique de Marat pendant la R\u00e9volution: (1789-1793) by Jacques De Cock, p. 538 ]</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Adolphe Thiers]] on Sunday morning 2 September: \"The keeper of the Abbaye sent away his children in the morning. Dinner was served to the prisoners two hours before the accustomed time; and the knives were taken from their plates.\"<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=yDIEAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA268&lpg=PA268&dq=insurrection+french+revolution&source=bl&ots=53T3ZQ6WRN&sig=bkjxrkuajhSUrkdDo5s9yYDBOpU&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj2v6qpwdDdAhWFLewKHeZbAecQ6AEwDXoECAAQAQ#v=onepage&q=Dinner%20was%20served&f=false The history of the French revolution, tr. with notes by Marie Joseph L. Adolphe Thiers, p. 144]</ref><ref>[https://archive.org/details/histoiredesgiron02gran/page/312 <!-- quote=187. --> Adolphe Granier de Cassagnac (1860) Histoire Des Girondins Et Des Massacres de Septembre, Band 2, p. 35-36, 53]</ref>\n\nSuch municipal and central government as existed in Paris in September 1792 was preoccupied with organizing volunteers, supplies, and equipment for the armies on the threatened frontiers. Accordingly, there was no attempt to assuage popular fears that the understaffed and easily accessed prisons were full of royalists who would break out and seize the city when the national guards and other citizen volunteers had left for the war. According to Madame Roland Danton responded to an appeal to protect the prisoners with the comment: \"To hell with the prisoners! They must look after themselves.\"<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=LEUuDAAAQBAJ&pg=PT172&lpg=PT172&dq=Discours+de+Danton,+%C3%A9dition+critique,+Paris,+1910&source=bl&ots=whpB9wTshS&sig=ACfU3U1IHSFzzGpCtwpYFLC6j-OP_UQ8zw&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiq86qLrPnmAhVNJlAKHbIjBZQQ6AEwD3oECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=2%20septembre&f=false Danton: Le mythe et l'histoire by Michel Biard, Herv\u00e9 Leuwers]</ref><ref>M. J. Sydenham ''The French Revolution'', B. T. Batsford Ltd, 1965, p. 121</ref><ref>R. Scurr (2006) Fatal Purity. Robespierre and the French Revolution, p. 243?</ref> On 3 September Roland said: \"Yesterday was a day that we should perhaps throw a veil on.\" The other member of the provisional government - [[\u00c9tienne Clavi\u00e8re|Clavi\u00e8re]], [[Pierre Henri H\u00e9l\u00e8ne Marie Lebrun-Tondu|Lebrun-Tondu]], [[Gaspard Monge|Monge]] and [[Joseph Marie Servan de Gerbey|Servan]], involved in organizing the country did not do much to stop the killing, or could not foresee or prevent these excesses. Mayor [[J\u00e9r\u00f4me P\u00e9tion de Villeneuve|P\u00e9tion de Villeneuve]] turned a blind eye when he visited Bic\u00eatre.<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=3gpBAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA346&lpg=PA346&dq=salpetriere+1792+septembre&source=bl&ots=Tcde_IezVW&sig=ACfU3U3GfJYAqoLuQFaakTNUfVDaMow5Ow&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiH6fnpupTnAhWHL1AKHeKYBYI4ChDoATADegQIBRAB#v=onepage&q=salpetriere%201792%20septembre&f=false M\u00e9moires sur les journ\u00e9es de septembre, 1792, p. 348 by  Fran\u00e7ois de Jourgniac Saint-M\u00e9ard, Paysac Fars marquise de Fausse-Lendry, Sicard (M. l'abb\u00e9, Roch Ambroise Cucurron), Antoine Gabriel Aim\u00e9 Jourdan]</ref> [[Olympe de Gouges]] and Brissot's newspaper were the only ones condemning the September murders.\n\n==Debate in the Convention==\n<!--P\u00e9tion was elected as president of the Convention on 20 September 1792.-->The Brissotins in the Convention first attacked Danton; he was asked to resign as minister on the 25th but forced to step down on 9 October. He kept his seat in Convention as deputy. Then the Brissotins decided to attack Robespierre and Marat. \n\nOn 29 October 1792, the Convention held an afterthought. [[Jean-Baptiste Louvet de Couvray]] accused Robespierre of creating a personality cult and interested in governing.<ref>S. Schama p. 649</ref> Robespierre was taken by surprise and had to be defended by Danton.<ref>R. Scurr (2006) Fatal Purity. Robespierre and the French Revolution, p. ?</ref> Robespierre was given eight days to reply. Marat was accused of being asocial and establishing dictatorship. On 5 November Robespierre stated that Marat had visited him only once since January.<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=iSMVAAAAQAAJ&printsec=frontcover&hl=de&source=gbs_atb#v=onepage&q&f=false Oeuvres, Band 2 by Maximilien Robespierre, p. 186, 188]</ref> He admitted the arrests [at the end of August] were illegal, as illegal as the revolution, the fall of the monarchy and the Bastille.<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=iLbxdDTtvvYC&pg=PA213&lpg=PA213&dq=29+october+1792+Robespierre+convention+illegal&source=bl&ots=YeB9T0c2Wt&sig=ACfU3U1TwVY2gmEQ6oqXPEYPwnnoEob4XQ&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwizuvvevf3mAhXIzaQKHXPLDzsQ6AEwBHoECAwQAQ#v=onepage&q=29%20october%201792%20Robespierre%20convention%20illegal&f=false The Eclectic Magazine of Foreign Literature, Science, and Art, Band 3, p. 213]</ref> He asked the Convention: \"Citizens, did you want a revolution without revolution?\" Robespierre, Danton and Marat insisted that the \"new bloodletting\" had been a spontaneous popular movement. Their opponents, the Girondins, spoke of a systematically planned conspiracy.<ref>J. Israel (2014) Revolutionary ideas, p. 271, 273</ref> Roland and Louvet were no longer admitted to the [[Jacobin Club]].<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=UT7WpHqpYbEC&pg=PA53&lpg=PA53&dq=Louvet+expelled+Jacobin+1792&source=bl&ots=69_VFweUSI&sig=ACfU3U0B0VVlIu9vL4xt39S7xHkcXxn0rA&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwivnpaRsODmAhVI3aQKHe4gBwQQ6AEwAHoECAYQAQ#v=onepage&q=Louvet%20expelled%20Jacobin%201792&f=false The Jacobin Republic 1792-1794 by Marc Bouloiseau, p. 53]</ref> \n\nThe political repercussions first injured the [[Girondin]]s (who seemed too moderate) and later the [[Jacobin]]s (who seemed too bloodthirsty).<ref>Georges Lefebvre, ''The French Revolution: From its Origins to 1793'' (1962), pp. 241\u201344, 269</ref> A new mayor [[Nicolas Chambon]] was installed on 1 December 1792. On 20 January 1793 Robespierre defended the massacres as necessary.<ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=6wPSAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA263&lpg=PA263&dq=20+janvier+1793+massacre&source=bl&ots=0vTic9B0ur&sig=ACfU3U3KOxgO1eb0Upxc7ookM373-i3spA&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj1-obsrJrnAhVDLlAKHT4yBtAQ6AEwAXoECAsQAQ#v=onepage&q=20%20janvier%201793%20massacre&f=false Oeuvres de Maximilien Robespierre, Band 9 by Maximilien Robespierre,p. 263-264]</ref> [[Louis XVI]] was guillotined on the next day. \n\nIt was Servan's proposal to bring armed volunteers from the provinces. He was arrested during the [[Reign of Terror|Terror]], but released in February 1795. In 1796 24 or 39 craftsmen and small businessmen were accused;<ref>P. Caron (1935), p. 107</ref> though only three were condemned.<ref>F. Bluche, p. 187, 210</ref> The vinegar maker Damiens got twenty years of imprisonment imposed.\n\n==Martyrs==\n{{Main|Holy September Martyrs}}\n[[Image:PrisonAbbayeChapel.jpg|thumb|200px|The abbey chapel in 1793.]]\nA group of 115 [[Clergy|churchmen]] killed in the Carmes Prison was [[Beatification|beatified]] by [[Pope Pius XI]] on 17 October 1926. Among the [[martyrs]] were Pierre-Louis de la Rochefoucauld, [[Ancient Diocese of Saintes|bishop of Saintes]]; [[Jean Marie du Lau|Jean-Marie du Lau d\u2019Alleman]], [[Ancient Diocese of Arles|archbishop of Arles]]; Fran\u00e7ois-Joseph de la Rochefoucauld, [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Beauvais|bishop of Beauvais]]; and [[Ambroise Chevreux]], the last superior-general of the monastic [[Congregation of Saint Maur]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://nominis.cef.fr/contenus/saint/1784/Saints-Martyrs-de-Septembre.html |title=Bienheureux Martyrs des Carmes |language=fr |website=Nominis |publisher=[[Catholic Church in France]] |access-date=2018-08-31 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Notes and citations==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n\n* [https://books.google.nl/books?id=fAMxAQAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=L.+Blanc+(1855)+Histoire+de+la+R\u00e9volution+Fran\u00e7aise,+vol+VII&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjbpLmghJPfAhWKmbQKHXS-BFMQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=L.%20Blanc%20(1855)%20Histoire%20de%20la%20R\u00e9volution%20Fran\u00e7aise%2C%20vol%20VII&f=false Blanc, L. (1855) Histoire de la R\u00e9volution Fran\u00e7aise, vol. VII. FUREURS DE LA GIRONDE]\n* Bluche, F. (1986) Septembre 1792 : logiques d'un massacre.\n* [[Pierre Caron (historian)|Caron, P.]] (1935) ''Les Massacres de Septembre'' \n* [https://books.google.nl/books?id=xpIpAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA272&dq=Robespierre++Temple+prison+September+1792&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjm56eAm_3fAhVLZVAKHUQABOcQ6AEIODAC#v=onepage&q=Robespierre%20%20Temple%20prison%20September%201792&f=false Israel, J. (2014) Revolutionary Ideas, p. 267-277]\n* Loomis, S. (1964) Paris in the Terror. New York: Dorset Press. {{ISBN|0-88029-401-9}} [https://www.questia.com/read/71902509/historical-dictionary-of-the-french-revolution-1789-1799 online]\n* Scott, S.F. & B. Rothaus, eds. (1985) ''Historical Dictionary of the French Revolution 1789\u20131799''.  Vol. 2 pp.&nbsp;891\u201397. \n* Tulard, J. & J-F. Fayard and A. Fierro (1998) ''Histoire et Dictionnaire de la R\u00e9volution Fran\u00e7aise''. {{ISBN| 2-221-08850-6}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* [https://warwick.ac.uk/fac/arts/history/students/modules/comparative_revolutions/programme/frenchrev2/furet_terror.pdf F. Furet (1989) Terror. In: A critical dictionary of the French Revolution] \n* Hibbert, Christopher (1980) ''The Days of the French Revolution''. William Morrow, New York.\n* [[Schama, Simon]] (1992) ''[[Citizens: A Chronicle of the French Revolution]]'' pp.&nbsp;629\u201339.\n* [https://h-france.net/rude/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/TackettVol4.pdf Tackett, Timothy (2011) \"Rumor and Revolution: The Case of the September Massacres\", ''French History and Civilization'' Vol. 4, pp. 54\u201364.]\n\n===Eyewitnesses===\n* [https://books.google.nl/books?id=mPANAAAAQAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Sta\u00ebl+Robespierre&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi_v7nI96jeAhXJKVAKHT7lDzAQ6AEIRTAE#v=onepage&q=destined%20to%20be%20massacred&f=false Madame de Sta\u00ebl (1818) Considerations on the Principal Events of the French Revolution, Band 2, p. 68]\n* [https://books.google.nl/books?id=MeRBAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA26&dq=la+verite+du+evenements+de+2+septembre&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjHkMi2n6ffAhWDqaQKHXrwCYc4ChDoAQgvMAE#v=onepage&q=la%20verite%20du%20evenements%20de%202%20septembre&f=false La V\u00e9rit\u00e9 toute enti\u00e8re sur les vrais acteurs de 2. Septembre 1792 par Jean Claude Hippolyte M\u00e9h\u00e9e de la Touche]\n* [http://libx.bsu.edu/cdm/compoundobject/collection/FrnchRev/id/614/rec/8 Histoire de la conjugation de Maximilien Robespierre]\n* [https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k64357941/f1n312.pdf?download=1 Nicolas-Edme Restif de la Bretonne (1793) Les nuits de Paris, ou Le spectateur nocturne, p. 371-394]\n* [http://chnm.gmu.edu/revolution/d/393/ The September Massacres witnessed by Earl Gower, a British diplomat]\n\n===Fictional accounts===\n* [[Charles Dickens|Dickens, Charles]], ''[[A Tale of Two Cities]]'' (1859).\n* Henty, George Alfred, ''In the Reign of Terror''.\n* Neville, Katherine, ''The Eight'' (1988).\n\n===See also===\n* [[The Legislative Assembly and the fall of the French monarchy]]\n\n==External links==\n* [https://erenow.net/modern/a-peoples-history-of-the-french-revolution/8.php Eric Hazan (2012) A People's History of the French Revolution. June to August 1792. The journ\u00e9e of 20 June, the Brunswick Manifesto, the taking of the Tuileries, the end of the monarchy, the September massacres]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20041125082150/http://campus.northpark.edu/history/WEBChron/westeurope/SeptMassacres.html \"The September Massacres : 2\u20137 Sept. 1792\"] (archived link)\n* [http://www.english.ucsb.edu/faculty/ayliu/research/around-1800/FR/carlyle.html Thomas Carlyle on the September Massacres]\n* [http://www.carnavalet.paris.fr/sites/default/files/styles/oeuvre_zoom/public/40057-2.jpg?itok=YFGt9YOT Massacre de 2, 3, 4, 5 et 6 septembre (print)]\n* [https://archive.org/details/lamassacresdesep00lenouoft/page/n11 Les massacres de Septembre (1910) by Lenotre, G]\n\n{{French Revolution navbox}}\n\n{{coord missing|France}}\n\n[[Category:1792 events of the French Revolution]]\