{"title_page": "James Anstruther", "text_new": "'''Sir James Anstruther of Anstruther''' (died 1606), was a Scottish landowner and courtier.\n\nAnstruther married Jean Scott.\n\nHe served as Master of Household to [[Anne of Denmark]], the wife of [[James VI of Scotland]].\n\nIn 1598 he joined a plan to resettle the [[Isle of Lewis]] with a group known as the [[Gentlemen Adventurers of Fife]].<ref>David Masson, ''Register of the Privy Council of Scotland: 1592-1599'', vol. 5 (Edinburgh, 1882), pp. 462-3, 467-8.</ref> \n\nHis heir was William Anstruther.\n\n[[Robert Anstruther (diplomat)|Sir Robert Anstruther]], the diplomat, was his second son.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anstruther, James}}\n[[Category:Court of James VI and I]]\n[[Category:16th-century Scottish people]]\n[[Category:17th-century Scottish people]]\n[[Category:Clan Anstruther]]\n", "text_old": "'''Sir James Anstruther of Anstruther''' (died 1606), was a Scottish landowner and courtier.\n\nAnstruther married Jean Scott.\n\nHe served as Master of Household to [[Anne of Denmark]], the wife of [[James VI of Scotland]].\n\nIn 1598 he joined a plan to resettle the [[Isle of Lewis]] with a group known as the [[Gentlemen Adventurers of Fife]].<ref>David Masson, ''Register of the Privy Council of Scotland: 1592-1599'', vol. 5 (Edinburgh, 1882), pp. 462-3, 467-8.</ref> \n\nHis heir was William Anstruther.\n\n[[Robert Anstruther (diplomat)|Sir Robert Anstruther]], the diplomat, was his second son.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anstruther, James}}\n[[Category:Court of James VI and I]]\n[[Category:16th-century Scottish people]]\n[[Category:17th-century Scottish people]]\n", "name_user": "Unoquha", "label": "safe", "comment": "cat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Anstruther"}
{"title_page": "List of jazz bassists", "text_new": "<!--Please don't add links to musicians for whom there is no article on Wikipedia; they will be removed.  There are a lot of gaps in Wikipedia's coverage of jazz, but either place a request for the article in question, or create one yourself. --><!--Please only add new entries for which there's an article; red-linked entries will be removed.  If a bassist really should be here, then start an article on him or her, and then add the link.-->\n[[File:Ron plays.JPG|thumb|upright|[[Ron Carter]], 2008.<br/> His appearances on over 2,000 albums make him one of the most-recorded bassists in jazz history.]]\nThis '''list of jazz bassists''' includes performers of the [[double bass]] and since the 1950s, and particularly in the jazz subgenre of [[jazz fusion]] which developed in the 1970s, [[electric bass]] players.\n\n[[File:Charles Mingus 1976 cropped.jpg|thumb|left|upright|[[Jazz]] bassist [[Charles Mingus]] was also an influential bandleader and composer whose musical interests spanned from bebop to free jazz.]]\nThe most influential [[jazz]] [[double bass]]ists from the 1940s and 1950s include bassist [[Jimmy Blanton]] (1918\u20131942) (a member of the [[Duke Ellington]] band); [[Oscar Pettiford]]   (1922\u20131960), who is considered by bassists and musicologists to be the first bebop bassist and the transitional link from the swing era to bebop. [[Ray Brown (musician)|Ray Brown]] (1926\u20132002), known for backing a number of [[bebop]]pers, including alto virtuoso [[Charlie Parker]]; [[Milt Hinton]] (1910-2000) and [[George Duvivier]] (1920-1985) who are the two most recorded bassists in jazz history, their respective careers spanning many eras and genres; a singular creative force was [[Wilbur Ware]] (1923\u20131979) legendary bassist with Monk and others, [[hard bop]] bassist [[Ron Carter]] (born 1937);  and [[Paul Chambers]] (1935\u20131969), a member of the [[Miles Davis Quintet]].\n\n[[File:Jaco pastorius 87.jpg|thumb|[[Jazz fusion]] bassist [[Jaco Pastorius]] was known for his expressive fretless [[electric bass]] playing.]]\nIn the experimental post 1960s eras, which saw the development of free jazz and jazz-rock fusion, some of the influential bassists included [[Charles Mingus]] (1922\u20131979) and [[free jazz]] and post-bop bassist [[Charlie Haden]] (1937-2014).\n\nIn the post-1970s era of [[jazz fusion|jazz-rock fusion]], the [[electric bass]] became an important jazz instrument; virtuoso [[Stanley Clarke]] (born 1951) played both the double bass and the electric bass. Fusion performer [[Jaco Pastorius]] (1951\u20131987) contributed to the development of a new approach to the fretless electric bass, adding a creative use of harmonics and chords, both while a member of the band [[Weather Report]] and in his solo recordings.\n\nIn the 1990s and 2000s, one of the new \"young lions\" for jazz bass was [[Christian McBride]] (born 1972).\nIn mid to late 2000s, another new \"young lion\" for jazz bass emerged [[Miles Mosley]] (born 1980) a member of the acclaimed Los Angeles collective, the West Coast Get Down.\n\n I would like to add to Bassist Christopher Amberger born in Waterbury Connecticut November 17, 1948 moved to Oakland in 1962 studied with with George Duke at Merritt College in Oakland California.\nGigging at night in West Oakland clubs  and roadhouses in Richmond with:\nSmiley Winters,Earl Andersa, Bill Connell, Tommy Warren , Leon HENDERSON part of the black arts music society in Oakland and the creative arts jazz ensemble  and dance guild, recorded First  television show on  KQED  about black revolutionary music in America. Recorded at The D Young museum in San Francisco with the prince Lachey ensemble featuring EDDIE HENDERSON for a Japanese record label in 1968\nWas on Numerous recordings for the Arhoolie record label.In 1969 won a downbeat scholarship to Berklee College of music.\n\nTHE Next 2\nyears in Boston,NYC East coast area:\nThen in Boston became active in the local jazz music scene\nPerformed in dozens of clubs, churches with Lenny Johnson, Andy Mckee, Tony Zano, Art Baron, Ricky  Ford, Ran Blake, Justo Almario,Michelle Wiley,Children at Play,\nVictor Brazil-Claudio Roditi\u2019s Boston Jazz  Orchestra,Featuring Herbie King,Kenny Werner, Keith O\u2019Quinn, Claudio Caribe, John LICATTA,Bill Drews, etc.\nThe Boston CBA, Mark Harvey at the old west church concerts series with,Kenny Dorham, Donald Byrd, Bob Nellems, KEVIN Tony, Mattie Mangrum etc\nNortheastern University concerts with Jackie Byard, J.R.Mitchell,Sid Simmons,\nJr Cook.\nPlayed in Apogee,\nTV shows w/Eddie Bee,\nPlayboy club in Boston w/Bob Winters, Black Avant-Garde Coffeehouse, Crown Manor, Jacks, Palls Mall,Jazz Woekshop, Debbie\u2019s, Estelle\u2019s  Poohs Pub,Unicorn ,Lenni\u2019s on the Turnpike,Freddy Gabriel\u2019s Christ Jazz missionary w/ David Ware,Bobbie Eldredge, Billy Pierce, Milton Marks,  EDDIE Alex, Stanton Davis etc.\n WBUR radio late  Night live jazz series on the radio with Oscar Jackson and Eric Jackson.\nWorcester Symphony, The Proposition,  South Shore music series,Monticello in Framingham w/Jerry Vale, Al  Martino, Stan Kenton Orchestra,  Jimmy Dorsey Orchestra Summer tours all over East Coast Florida to Maine,Michael Polaco with Richie Havens Tours,Hasty Pudding Theatrical  in Cambridge and Bermuda, Sammy Davis Junior at Hyannis Sheraton, Provincetown, \nRecording session for ESP w/Rocky Birigawa And concert at NYU in NYC w/ Don Alias,Jeremy Steig, Carter Collins,\nJumma Santos.\n\nTo Be Contiued.The next 48 years I will continue to add on Thank you\n\n==A==\n<!--Please don't add links to musicians for whom there is no article on Wikipedia; they will be removed.  There are a lot of gaps in Wikipedia's coverage of jazz, but either place a request for the article in question, or create one yourself. --><!--Please only add new entries for which there's an article; red-linked entries will be removed.  If a bassist really shou